<CAPTION>  Map; MAP: Mercury News; Redistricting San Jose; The Rose Garden is the prize
in a turf war over how to redraw San Jose's city council districts. The
majority of the city's redistricting committee favors putting it in District 6
as shown here.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL; POLITICS; GOVERNMENT; NEIGHBORHOOD; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The Rose Garden, an affluent seedbed for San Jose mayors, is emerging as
prized turf for city council map makers in a debate that could jar the
political base of Councilman David Pandori.;    The neighborhood, named for a
city garden at Naglee and Dana avenues, is bounded roughly by Interstate 880,
The Alameda, Bascom Avenue and the Shasta-Hanchett area. It now straddles two
districts: Pandori's downtown and Councilwoman Nancy Ianni's Willow Glen
district.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THORNY ISSUE OF S.J. REDISTRICTING MAY UPROOT
MAYOR-RICH ROSE GARDEN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Pandori's chunk includes the West Hedding Street home of Mayor Susan
Hammer, who represented the district until last year. Former Mayor Janet Gray
Hayes lives close by, and other mayors have also come from the garden's
stately streets. The area is mostly white and relatively wealthy.;    With
strong support from the Rose Garden, Pandori won a very close election last
November.;    Now 1990 census data and a majority of council-appointed map
makers threaten to strip the garden from Pandori's district and substitute
heavily Hispanic Alviso. The result would unite the garden in Ianni's domain.;
   The proposed map is one of the first in San Jose's once-a-decade political
reorganization. In general, district lines must move from west to east this
year to account for swift growth in Berryessa, Alum Rock, Edenvale and
Evergreen.;    The majority's map is on view in a public hearing tonight,
along with another drafted by John Marshall Collins, an attorney Pandori named
to the redistricting panel. His map would keep Pandori's half of the Rose
Garden in the downtown district.;    Pandori would not comment. Collins could
not be reached Wednesday. Ianni said she wouldn't "speculate.";    But
Hammer's redistricting strategist, Bob Brownstein, offered this: "If I was
David, I wouldn't view this as a potentially mortal blow." Brownstein reasoned
that Pandori has plenty of time -- three-plus years -- to work with a new
constituency.;    The 11-member panel must finish a plan by mid-July. The map
will be reviewed next by a small group named by Hammer, and then the council
must vote on it. So plenty of politicking remains before a new map is
approved.;    Other key changes include extending Blanca Alvarado's Alum Rock
district up the eastern hills to Alum Rock Park and thrusting Joe Head's
Almaden district north from Blossom Hill Road to Capitol Expressway.;  IF
YOU'RE INTERESTED;    The Redistricting Advisory Commission meets tonight at 7
p.m. in the city council chambers, 801 N. First St.  </TEXT>
