<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; STATE; LEGISLATURE; ZONING; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The number of predominantly Hispanic city council districts in San Jose would
drop from two to one under a plan approved Thursday night by the commission
charged with redrawing political boundaries.;    Over the objections of
Councilwoman Blanca Alvarado's representative on the 2-month-old commission,
the 11-member body adopted a map that will reduce the number of Hispanics in
Councilman David Pandori's District 3 from the current 52 percent to 48
percent.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HISPANICS MAY LOSE 1 OF 2 DISTRICTS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "I don't think we tried hard enough" to keep the district predominantly
Hispanic, said Angel Rios, the Alvarado appointee.;    But John Marshall
Collins, Pandori's commissioner, cried foul, arguing that Rios was trying to
boost the Hispanic percentage at the risk of politically splitting
long-established communities.;    "It's just race, race, race," Collins said.
"That's not the only factor here. I cannot accept it. . . . It's not the way
we do things in this country.";    The only remaining predominantly Hispanic
district would be Alvarado's District 5 on the East Side, where Hispanic
percentages would drop only slightly to 56 percent.;    One reason that the
Hispanic percentages in the two districts are decreasing is that Asian voting
power is increasing. While the percentage of Hispanics in the city grew from
23.2 to 26.6 between 1980 and 1990, the percentage of Asians increased from
8.2 to 19.5 percent.;    If the city council adopts the commission's plan,
Pandori would pick up the Alviso and North San Jose areas from District 4,
Shirley Lewis' northeast district. District 3 would also cross Highway 101 at
Santa Clara Street, a move aimed at unifying the Portuguese community on both
sides of 101.;    Under the commission's plan, Pandori will only lose a small
Rose Garden area near Park and Naglee avenues.;    At one point several weeks
ago, the commission was leaning toward handing most of Pandori's Rose Garden
constituents over to Councilwoman Nancy Ianni. But Pandori, who won a narrow
victory last November over Pete Carrillo with strong Rose Garden support, won
on that score.;    One reason that Pandori's district had to change so much
was that Councilwoman Pat Sausedo's district grew so fast during the past
decade. Decreasing the number of people in her district creates ripples
throughout the others.;    Aside from Rios -- who was supported in a letter by
Ray Villareal, Councilman Jim Beall's appointee -- the only other dissenter in
approving the final map Thursday was Collins. But the attorney said he
objected for a different reason. He thought Pandori's district had been
twisted out of shape.;    Rios' suggestion to increase the number of Hispanics
to at least 50 percent would have involved tinkering with the boundaries even
more.;    The majority of the commission eventually agreed that District 3's
lines had been redrawn enough -- and they decided to leave the Hispanic
percentage at 48 percent.;    The once-a-decade map changes will now be
reviewed by a small panel named by Mayor Susan Hammer. Then the city council
must approve it.  </TEXT>
