<LEADPARA>  Aided by powerhouse attorney Joaquin Avila, a Latino political action group
Thursday unveiled a new map of San Jose City Council districts that aims to
protect Hispanic voting blocs while bolstering chances a Hispanic could soon
capture the downtown seat.;    Avila has made political history in several
recent voting-rights cases, notably a successful Hispanic challenge to
Watsonville's city council electoral system.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LATINO GROUP HAS NEW MAP
S.J. COUNCIL DISTRICTS TARGETED FOR CHANGE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The Hispanic he boosts could be Pete Carrillo, who wore several hats while
watching the City Hall news conference from the sidelines.;    Carrillo is
president of the Latino Issues Forum and an aide to Councilwoman Blanca
Alvarado, who represents the majority Hispanic Alum Rock district. He is also
a politician of no small ambition, who lost a razor-close race last November
to downtown Councilman David Pandori.;    However, Carrillo gave the
obligatory denial Thursday to suggestions of any personal political
motivations. His interest, he said, lay only with his political action group.
He said he had given no thought to running again since November.;    At least
one observer wasn't buying the disavowal.;    "They're looking for an edge
that a Hispanic candidate can get in the next election," Councilman Jim Beall
said. "And the guy that's the candidate is the head of the group.";    Once a
decade, the city must reorganize its 10 city council districts, responding to
new census data. San Jose's map-making is in the midst of a tortuous series of
hearings and revisions that will wind up in the council's lap this fall.;
The Latino Issues Forum map would make 53 percent of the downtown district
Hispanic -- a level equal to the current map but about 5 percent more than a
proposed map drawn last month by a redistricting panel appointed by city
commissioners.;    A majority of the panel argues that for the good of the
city the downtown district needs to lose some Hispanic population. But that
argument doesn't sway Avila, who gave a guest lecture last spring to the
redistricting commission. "We have a very serious problem with taking away
Latino population from (the downtown district)," said Avila, who hinted at
legal challenges if he doesn't get his way.;    Alvarado is ensconced in a 57
percent Hispanic district that is generally considered a safe Latino seat.
Avila said the downtown could reach that level in the next 10 years if it
remains intact.;    Ironically, Pandori, Carrillo's one-time opponent, is
touting another alternative to protect the Hispanic population.;    A map
drawn by Pandori's commission representative, John Marshall Collins, proposes
a 53 percent Hispanic concentration. The chief difference between his map and
Avila's is that Pandori would not put Alviso, the city's northern extremity,
in the downtown district.;    Pandori could not be reached for comment.  </TEXT>
