<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; MAYOR; CITY; POLITICS; COUNCIL; MINORITY; POPULATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Mayor Susan Hammer on Monday announced her new political map for the 10 San
Jose City Council districts -- a plan that drew endorsements from Hispanic
leaders, muted praise from some Asians and outrage from the downtown
councilman.;   Hammer said at a news conference that she expects the council
-- which now includes one Mexican-American member and one of Hispanic and
Japanese ancestry -- will add at least two or three minority members by the
next time the map is redrawn, in 2001.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HAMMER DRAWS PRAISE, CRITICISM IN PROPOSAL FOR
REALIGNED DISTRICTS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Hammer's map comes after other citizen-drawn maps -- including one
recommended by a council-appointed panel -- percolated through City Hall. Her
map must still be approved by the city council at a meeting Dec. 3.;   The
mayor continued to stress what has become the dominant theme of her first-year
administration: political pluralism.;   To San Jose's minority group members,
which number more than half the populace, she said, "The goal of the plan I
present to you today is to give these new voices a powerful message: The doors
of City Hall are, and will be, open to you.";   Redistricting is like
dominoes. Push one, and nine fall. In this case, Hammer pushed the downtown.
She concentrated the Hispanic population as much as possible in the district
represented by rookie Councilman David Pandori, raising the Hispanic
percentage from 52.6 percent to 55 percent and answering complaints aired last
summer by the Latino Issues Forum and its attorney, voting rights specialist
Joaquin Avila.;   This did not raise Pandori's ire. In fact, he proposed
nearly the same Hispanic percentage as Hammer -- 54.2 percent.;   What burned
him was that Hammer bumped some neighborhoods southwest of Stockton Avenue,
which he considers part of the downtown core, into a different district. Under
Hammer's plan, half the Rose Garden, Garden Alameda and College Park -- which
includes Bellarmine College Preparatory school -- would join the district
represented by Willow Glen Councilwoman Nancy Ianni.;   "They're part of the
central area, and Susan has drawn a map that ignores that fact," said Pandori,
arguing that those neighborhoods need an open door with the same council
member who represents the nearby airport and sports arena.;   Hammer, asked
about potential council critics, said: "I don't think any city council member
is threatened by it.";   Decisions on the downtown district reverberated
throughout the map. Hammer left Alviso and the industrial corridor in North
San Jose in the Berryessa district represented by Shirley Lewis, instead of
grafting it to downtown. Mayoral aides said they believed rapidly growing
North San Jose might ultimately dilute the downtown's Hispanic population.;
The consequence, some map experts said, was that Lewis' District 4 grew less
in Asian strength than it might have. District 4 will now be 37.4 percent
Asian, an increase from the current 35.4 percent, but still less than the 40
percent some Asian leaders wanted. In the Evergreen district to the southeast,
Hammer pushed the Asian percentage from 30.2 percent to 35.3 percent, again
short of the 40 percent target.;   "We have to acknowledge her effort. We
can't say she didn't pay attention," said Lam Duc Nguyen, deputy executive
director of the Indochinese Resettlement &amp; Cultural Center, who lobbied Hammer
Friday for higher numbers.;   The mayor and her aides, explaining why they
couldn't support the 40-40 Asian goal, said it was unrealistic.;   Nguyen
accepted the criticism. "It's painful, but it may be true.";   Then there was
Councilman George Shirakawa, who stood and smiled at a Latino Issues Forum
news conference, endorsing the mayor's plan even though he was handed a
political lemon. His District 7 now jumps east of Highway 101, embracing two
police-targeted Project Crackdown neighborhoods between the freeway and King
Road -- Lanai-Cunningham and Stonegate. Shirakawa already has two crackdown
areas on his hands, Santee and Los Arboles.;   As he ducked out of the
conference, Shirakawa was asked whether he liked straddling 101. He replied:
"For the good of the community, yes, it's a fair way to go. I'll leave it at
that."; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; The city council will discuss the mayor's map at
7:30 p.m. today in the council chambers at City Hall, 801 N. First St. Final
approval is scheduled for Dec. 3.  </TEXT>
