<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; COAST; NEIGHBORHOOD; POLITICS; ECONOMY; CHANGE; SUPPORT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Savas Alvarez foresees the salvation of Alviso, the San Jose bayshore hamlet
swamped by toxics and code-enforcement problems, where abandoned boats
languish in the mud and gutters and sidewalks still seem a luxury.;   The
salvation, says Alvarez, is politics.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ALVISO SEEKS POLITICAL CLOUT
S.J. REDISTRICTING PLANS POSE PLENTY OF QUESTIONS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "We can make Alviso a political campaign issue," said Alvarez, 41, a
carpenter and president of the Alviso Community Organization. "That way we can
get commitments from the candidates: What are you going to do for us?";   The
first step, however, is for the city to decide whether there will be a
campaign next year. That question is now in the hands of San Jose's political
mapmakers, who are redrawing district lines for the first time in a decade,
and deciding who will represent this North Side neighborhood.;   It is but one
of several issues that will soon land in the city council's lap, as
redistricting comes to a head. Tonight a special citizens panel is expected to
reject a map of council lines that was drafted last summer by a redistricting
commission. This development will leave Mayor Susan Hammer and her 10 council
members with these problems:;   (check) Should Alviso and the long First
Street corridor north of Highway 101 move from Shirley Lewis' Berryessa
district to David Pandori's downtown district? The Alviso issue is
particularly sensitive because it's been neglected by most politicians for the
24 years it has been part of San Jose.;   Lewis will leave the council after
next year, meaning her seat is up for election; Pandori just won his seat last
year, so that position isn't up for grabs again until 1994. The commission's
map would have given Alviso to Pandori. Some influential old-timers, including
Richard Santos, son of a former Alviso mayor and a Lewis foe, would rather go
with Pandori.;   (check) Should the downtown district shift from nearly 53
percent Hispanic population, as it stands now, to 48 percent, as the
commission proposed? Many Latinos say this move would dilute their voting
strength. Voting rights attorney Joaquin Avila is pressuring the city to back
down.;   (check) Should the Asian populations within Berryessa and within Pat
Sausedo's District 8 be concentrated to 40 percent? Some Asian legal experts
share Avila's ire and, likewise, want their political clout to reflect their
community's phenomenal population growth. But the Asian communities, unlike
the Hispanics, are geographically more dispersed, making a majority Asian
district unlikely.;   The review panel, a group of five experts appointed by
Hammer to study the commission's work, is expected to formally reject the
draft map tonight because, in part, these dilemmas remain unresolved.;
Alviso is only one of several issues, but it could touch a soft spot with city
officials, who are mindful that the neighborhood is not as well served as it
could be.;   Its population, now more than 2,000, is heavily Hispanic. Its
voting clout, in a district of about 80,000, is small. Its symbolic
significance is large.;   "It would be better if it was left in District 4,"
said Shirley Lewis, speaking of her own council turf. "District 3 (downtown)
is such a complicated district, and Alviso needs special attention.";   IF
YOU'RE INTERESTED; The redistricting review panel meets at 6:30 p.m. today in
City Hall, 801 N. First St.  </TEXT>
