<DESCRIPT>  ETHNIC; POPULATION; CHANGE; RELATION; POLITICS; SAN-JOSE; ANALYSIS  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Think of San Jose's city council districts as political amoebas, a collection
of 10 elongated, compacted, or panhandled map blobs about to fuse, divide and
re-form for the first time in a decade.;    As the city's center of gravity
tilts eastward, the amoebas must follow, an immutable fact that a panel of
newly appointed citizen mapmakers is beginning to learn.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  POWER FLOWS EAST
S.J. DISTRICTS BEING REDRAWN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Analysis
See also related stories on P. 6B of this section  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     New district boundaries drawn over the next few months are likely to
reflect the emerging power of the city's Asian and Hispanic communities. They
may also show how politicians maneuver to protect or expand their base of
support and how neighborhoods guard old identities or sink new roots.;
Politicians and mapmakers predict most new districts will resemble their
forerunners. There is neither outcry about flagrant gerrymandering from the
last map nor talk of starting the new one from scratch.;    But a few
districts will change radically, notably the home base of Councilwoman Pat
Sausedo. District 8, the city's largest in area and population, is home to
Evergreen and a long swath of hills and open space to the south and east.;
The city estimates that District 8 now has 103,720 people, an outsize chunk of
the city's 1990 population of 780,000.;    It takes little math to figure the
population equilibrium point for new districts: 78,000. Sausedo's district
needs to lose about 25,000 people. As her district goes, so goes the rest of
the city. Pinch something from it, and ripples will flow everywhere else.;
If an axis were drawn through San Jose from northwest to southeast along The
Alameda and Monterey Highway, it would cut districts roughly into two kinds:
to the northeast, those above the population equilibrium; to the southwest,
those below it.;    The counterweight to District 8 is District 9. The
Cambrian area, represented by Councilman Jim Beall, must gain nearly 20,000
people. Ray Villarreal, a real estate lobbyist whom Beall picked for the
11-member Redistricting Advisory Commission, said he figures the district may
move south and east.;    But he is loath to invade the north. "I would hate to
see any splitting of Willow Glen," Villarreal said.;    The last round of
redistricting nibbled at the southern fringe of Willow Glen. So Villarreal
raises a fundamental question: Which neighborhoods are inviolable, and which
may be carved?;    Another key issue is race and ethnicity. Recent
anti-discrimination lawsuits in Watsonville and Los Angeles have paved the way
for an ethnic political revolution in those cities, dramatically opening the
city council to Hispanic communities.;    San Jose points instead to a slower
political evolution. Two Hispanics already sit on the city council here. Three
other districts -- downtown, Berryessa and Evergreen -- are less than
half-Anglo and growing ripe for a successful minority candidate.;    There are
two Hispanics on the advisory panel, named last month by the city council to
draw a recommended map, but there are no Asians or blacks.;    An attorney for
San Jose's Asian Law Alliance, Jacquelyn Maruhashi, has warned the panel that
it should listen to Asians, the city's fastest-growing minority. "If we're not
able to get input into the process, you're inviting a lawsuit," she said.;
On Thursday, mapmakers got their first glimpse of what new districts could
look like. Five hypothetical maps drawn by city planners showed boundaries
migrating north and east in several configurations.;    All five showed
Alviso, the city's northern extremity, migrating from Berryessa's District 4
to downtown's District 3. Downtown and Alviso would make an odd marriage
indeed, but planners stressed that the maps were only a non-political first
stab.;    Some officials don't believe the maps will change much at all. Bob
Brownstein, a policy aide to Mayor Susan Hammer, predicted changes would be
"routine and technical, a little shifting of the margins.";    Such margins
could prove crucial. Hammer herself benefited from a marginal change 10 years
ago, when a finger of land southwest of The Alameda was tacked onto District
3. Previously, The Alameda bounded the district. The finger happened to
include Hammer's West Hedding Street home, and she won the downtown council
seat in the next election.;    The mayor denies that she influenced that
decision, pivotal to her career. "I probably was, at best, oblivious to the
process that was going on," she said.;    This time around, Councilman David
Pandori will be watching the downtown margins closely.;    In November,
Pandori, an Anglo, beat a Hispanic candidate by a few hundred votes in a
Hispanic-majority district. Some say Pandori's re-election prospects in 1994
hinge on the movement of edges of his district, which needs to lose nearly
8,000 people.;    Pandori dismisses such talk. He sees downtown as the city's
most coherent district, and he sees its lines as rock-solid. "It would bother
me if people started drawing the boundaries in a way that didn't reflect
geography," he said.;    Councilman Joe Head may also need to watch his
margins. Head, the only council member eligible for re-election in 1992, won
his Almaden seat by 5 percent in 1988.;    Two other council members who could
run again in 1994 -- Trixie Johnson in District 1, the West Valley, and George
Shirakawa in District 7, central San Jose -- were elected by wider majorities.
They have less to lose.;    Because of a new two-term limit, the rest of the
council must step down by the end of 1994. The limit may squelch some
redistricting politics. Incumbents can't dig trenches when they must leave
office every eight years. But people jockeying to replace them will certainly
try to bend mapmakers' ears.;     IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The redistricting
panel meets most Thursdays through July 11 at City Hall, Room 204. All
meetings are public. Its first public hearing is set for May 23 at 7 p.m. in
the council chambers.  </TEXT>
