<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; ELECTION; POLITICS; ZONING; CONTROVERSY; MEETING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  While a showdown over Hispanic voting power faces San Jose City Council map
makers, the political road show called redistricting arrives Tuesday evening
in Alum Rock, the heart of the city's Hispanic community.;   The hearing, the
first of three this month, gives the public a chance to say exactly which
neighborhoods should be represented by which council districts, and whether
proposed political maps fragment or unify discrete interest groups.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HEARING ON S.J. DISTRICTS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Once every 10 years, the city must redraw its 10 council districts. This
year more than ever before, San Jose and governments throughout California are
being pressed to grant the new power that Hispanics claim as their due.;   In
San Jose, the trickiest map is undoubtedly District 3, home of downtown
Councilman David Pandori, which encompasses San Jose International Airport,
part of the Rose Garden and poorer areas near Interstate 280 and Highway 101.;
  Plan trimmed percentage; Two months ago, a majority of 11 council-appointed
map makers drew a downtown district that sliced the Hispanic population by
one-twentieth, from just under 53 percent to 48 percent. This group said the
fraction was too small to make a difference. Instead, it touted the five
districts it drew with combined ethnic majorities -- lumping blacks, Asians
and Hispanics together.;   Still, the Latino Issues Forum, headed by former
downtown council candidate Pete Carrillo, cried foul. Backed by voting-rights
experts, the forum last month made public a plan to save the Hispanic bloc.;
Other maps, including one Pandori supports, also make a Hispanic majority.
Asians, too, are pushing for more power in the city's north and east.;   One
more complication: Five council seats are up for grabs next year -- four of
them vacant -- and potential candidates are anxious not to be bumped from
their power base.;   Mayor's review panel; The whole matter now sits with
another panel, a five-member review board named by Mayor Susan Hammer. The
council must agree on the final map later this fall.;   The panel, which is
hosting this month's hearings, includes Fernando Zazueta, a Hispanic attorney
and Hammer's campaign treasurer; Hope Nakamura, a board member for the Asian
Law Alliance; Lela Llorens, a black San Jose State faculty member; and two
whites, Peter Haas, a San Jose State political scientist; and Judge John
Kennedy, retired from Santa Clara County Superior Court.;   Some panel members
reached by phone Sunday avoided the Hispanic question. Not Zazueta. "It's
clear to me that the (first mapmaking group) seems not to have paid heed to
one of its principal reasons for being: not to dilute, if possible, one
particular voting group," he said.; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The Redistricting
Review Panel will hold three public hearings: 7 p.m. Tuesday at the Eastside
Senior Center, 2150 Alum Rock Ave.; 7 p.m. Thursday at Pioneer High School
cafeteria, 1290 Blossom Hill Road; and 7 p.m. Sept. 19 at City Hall, 801 N.
First St.  </TEXT>
