<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL; POLITICS; ZONING; CHANGE; POPULATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  In approving San Jose's new political map for the 1990s, the city council was
forced Tuesday night to make a wrenching choice between slicing small
increments of power from ethnic minority groups and shaving neighborhoods from
council members who fought to keep them.;   The debate ended in Mayor Susan
Hammer's favor, as the council voted 10-1 to adopt a map barely changed from
the one she unveiled two weeks ago. The map held fast to ethnic population
counts some judge crucial to moving more Asians and Hispanics into City Hall.
Only Councilwoman Shirley Lewis voted no.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. POLITICAL PLURALISM PREVAILS AS HAMMER-BACKED
MAP IS ADOPTED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The mayor was tugged in two opposite directions -- neighborhood unity vs.
political pluralism -- two themes that served her well in her election a year
ago. It was a difficult choice because the margins on both sides were so
small.;   On one hand were council members David Pandori, Trixie Johnson and
Lewis, who argued for bringing a small piece of the Berryessa School District
back into the Berryessa council district and the Garden Alameda neighborhood
back into the downtown council district.;   On the other were Hammer and the
rest of the council, who argued against cutting two-tenths of a percentage
point from Berryessa's Asian population (finally adopted at 37.4 percent) and
against cutting one-tenth of a point from the downtown's Hispanic population
(adopted at 55.0 percent).;   Council members said that the number of people
at stake amounted to less than 100 people in each case, from districts of
about 80,000 apiece.;   Said Pandori, who voted for Hammer's map in the end
after supporting two failed amendments: "All of us truly do find ourselves
unified in trying to maximize minority population and keeping neighborhoods
together. The trick has been balancing those two things.";   Hammer refused to
budge. "I cannot reduce the ethnic voting power in any district . . . to
accommodate the interests of one small neighborhood," she said.;   But
neighborhoods, no matter how small, are the bread and butter of every council
member, and it clearly pained some to vote against the residential interests.
"Those of us who voted on the other side also voted in the best interests of
the city," said Councilman Joe Head, explaining his tilt in this case toward
the minority groups.;   The mayor's map had the backing of Hispanic political
activists, but some Asian leaders criticized it for not pushing their clout
further in Evergreen and Berryessa.;   The Berryessa issue may take on more
political significance in next year's council elections. Carm Grande, a
candidate to replace Lewis, spoke out for the councilwoman and the Berryessa
School District.;   Margie Fernandes, a top mayoral aide who is also running
in Berryessa, did not speak out at the hearing but said that she backed Hammer
on the issue.;   In the end, nearly every council member lined up with the
mayor, including those who did well by themselves and those who lost back-room
battles. Councilman Jim Beall got last-minute help when the mayor moved his
Cambrian Park District 9 eastward to Guadalupe River. Beall, not
coincidentally, is planning a $325,000 bike trail and footpath along the
river.;   Then there was Vice Mayor Pat Sausedo, who supported Hammer's map
despite losing control over a controversial new neighborhood of up to 990
homes she supports for Edenvale. "We are not all going to have every little
aspect of what we would like," Sausedo said. "But redistricting is not
supposed to accommodate all of our personal desires."  </TEXT>
