<LEADPARA>  Two of San Jose's spiciest political issues -- redrawing city council
boundaries and managing growth in South San Jose -- merged Thursday when Mayor
Susan Hammer picked the winner of a turf war between two councilwomen for
control of a major new neighborhood proposed in Edenvale.;   The struggle
between Pat Sausedo and Judy Stabile topped a dramatic week at City Hall --
one that saw a major development proposal hit an unforeseen roadblock thrown
up by a school district and a new political map for San Jose that promises
increased clout for ethnic minority groups.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MAYOR SETTLES TURF WAR ON S.J. COUNCIL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Analysis  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Vice Mayor Sausedo, who supports the housing proposal by Shea Homes and
Gibson Speno Co., clashed with Stabile, who is fighting to keep the 92 acres
zoned for industry.;   Each wanted the land in her district, and Hammer, after
waffling last weekend, said Thursday she would side with Stabile, meaning that
the developers will face much tougher negotiations over zoning for the land if
the proposal passes a key planning hurdle on Dec. 10.;   Ironically, the mayor
supports the development of up to 990 new homes, which passed the council Nov.
14 on an 8-3 vote. The project now faces another review because of 11th-hour
protests aired earlier this week by the cash-crunched Oak Grove School
District, which serves the neighborhood.;   The Sausedo-Stabile struggle is
perhaps the most interesting political development to emerge since Hammer
unveiled her map for San Jose's 10 city council districts Monday.;   The
council, which solidly supports most of Hammer's redistricting plan, will vote
on it Dec. 3.;   Other bits of political intrigue surrounding the plan
include:;   (check) A bid by Asian interest groups to get the mayor to raise
voting power by a few critical percentage points in the Berryessa and
Evergreen districts. By bumping densely Asian apartment complexes between
Mabury and McKee roads from the Alum Rock district to Berryessa, some say, the
Asian population in the northern district could creep up past the 37.4 percent
Hammer gave it.;   (check) A bid by downtown Councilman David Pandori to
reclaim nearly 3,000 mostly white residents in the College Park and Garden
Alameda neighborhoods. Hammer had moved them into a district west of
Pandori's, in a move aimed at concentrating Hispanic strength downtown.;
(check) A gentlemen's agreement cut between councilmen Jim Beall and Joe Head,
who represent southwest San Jose. Beall agreed to let Head keep control of the
old Almaden Winery site, where a park and community center are planned just
south of their common district boundary, Blossom Hill Road. And Head raised no
qualms when Beall moved east, across Almaden Expressway, snaring a piece of
the Guadalupe River.;   The cooperation between Beall and Head contrasted with
the battle between Sausedo and Stabile.;   Sausedo represents District 8,
largely based in Evergreen, north of the Silver Creek Hills and nestled
against the Diablo Range. Her current lines also include a large part of
Edenvale, between the Silver Creek Hills and Monterey Highway, jumping over
Highway 101.;   Sausedo now controls the acreage for the developers' housing
proposal and has been a force in shepherding the controversial project past
some significant barriers at City Hall, including the objections of top
administration officials who want the land kept preserved for the city's
industrial tax base.;   Stabile represents District 2, based northeast of the
Santa Teresa Ridge and west of the proposed housing.;   A map Hammer floated
privately to council members last week gave Stabile all of Edenvale, through
the Silver Creek hillsides, which form a natural barrier to Sausedo's
territory.;   But the mayor said Sausedo objected strongly to giving up the
territory, so the boundary was switched over the weekend. When Hammer
announced her map at a news conference, it showed Sausedo's district reaching
Coyote Creek, which happens to be the western property line for the
developers.;   This meant that Stabile would essentially represent all the
homes between the Santa Teresa and Silver Creek hills except those proposed by
the developers. Stabile protested.;   "I want it from ridgeline to ridgeline,"
she said.;   This week, Hammer reversed her position -- though her support for
the project remains solid.;   But the mayor conceded that Stabile could now
play a key role in the proposal's future.;   "Council members have a lot of
power in land use issues and working with the planning department," Hammer
said. "They can either expedite them and make them happen or they can throw up
roadblocks.";   Sausedo and Stabile could not be reached for comment Thursday
afternoon. Steve Speno, spokesman for the developers, was also unavailable.  </TEXT>
