<TEXT>     In the down times between high-tech conventions and political dinners, the
San Jose McEnery Convention Center rents space for an increasingly popular
activity: Hispanic dances (In memory of the Lord Mayor, we forebear dwelling
on the irony). In fact, the dances have become so popular that the city
officials have been forced to plan a drawing among competing promoters for
1992 dates. The drawing itself may be a bit, well, tilted. According to a
letter we obtained from convention-meister Ellie Oppenheim, only three of 30
interested promoters are eligible. They are Al Rodriguez, of LUZ-AL
Promotions; Ari Evans of El Mundo International and Amador Bustos of Radio
KLOK/KBRG. We asked Jim McBride, Oppenheim's deputy, why those three got
special treatment. "They've all been here in the past and had successful
events," he said. "We don't want to saturate the market and kill everybody
off."; WHITE CHRISTMAS;   Wanna know the real spirit of Christmas? Get out
your handkerchiefs. The lead from a Santa Clara County press release last week
read, "The holiday season of giving marks the time for a very important
year-end contribution: Santa Clara County property taxes." . . . Add another
name to the list of potential candidates in city council District 6, Willow
Glen and the Rose Garden: Tom Hayes, an official with Applied Materials. Hayes
is not without friends in politics: Applied Materials' CEO is James Morgan,
husband of State Sen. Becky Morgan . . . Finally, it's fair to say that
Sunnyvale City Councilman Stan Kawczynski desperately needs -- or needed -- a
proofreader. Before the recent election, Kawczynski mailed out a two-page
leaflet that trumpeted his achievements with atrocious spelling. A few
examples: He talked about the threat of groundwater contimination; pledged to
be more resposive to the needs of citizens, underscored his committment to
Sunnyvale; and, maybe best of all, said that his proffession was as a
financial adviser.; MASSED TRANSIT;   The fate of Santa Clara County bus line
72 may not seem like earth-shattering stuff: But since all politics is local,
even this obscure route through downtown had its moment. With the consent of
the city council, San Carlos Street is about to be closed through the San Jose
State University campus on a trial basis. Because line 72 now runs down San
Carlos, its route must be changed. The transit people initially proposed
running the 72 south on 13th Street to Reed Street, and then westward to
First. This went directly through the Naglee Park neighborhood, vigorously
defended by Supervisor Zoe Lofgren and Councilman David Pandori. At Pandori's
suggestion, the transit people now seem ready to accept a new alignment that
would bring the route across San Carlos to 11th Street; north on 11th and west
on San Fernando Street. Before they did, an intriguing group of power-brokers
actually rode the 72 through the neighborhood to judge how difficult the turns
were. Transit spokeswoman Deborah Wetter said they included transit chief
Larry Reuter, former Supervisor Susanne Wilson, Pandori, and Lofgren aide Mike
Boenninghausen.; UNPREFERRED RISK;   Amid the carping about credit card rates,
one class of loan victim has been forgotten: the politician. Or more
accurately, the politician's donors. Consider the case of San Jose
Councilwoman Blanca Alvarado. Alvarado's campaign records show that she loaned
her re-election campaign $15,000 in two installments last year. They show she
repaid the loans with $1,363 in interest, which works out to between 22 and 25
percent per year. Is Alvarado getting rich off her own campaign? Hardly. The
councilwoman says she obtained the loans from Plaza Bank and Cupertino
National Bank. And that was the interest they charged her.  </TEXT>
