<LEADPARA>  David Pandori emerged as the No. 1 naysayer in his rookie year on the San Jose
City Council, earning venom, irritation and bemused respect from his 10
colleagues.;   George Shirakawa, whose first year was an apprenticeship in
complex neighborhood and minority issues, learned that working on the council
sometimes is a drag.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. COUNCIL ROOKIES WIN RANCOR, RESPECT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     And Trixie Johnson, the third council newcomer in 1991, established herself
as an environmentalist and slow-growth voice on a council that is leaning more
and more toward business and development interests.;   These three are the
first wave of new faces for what promises to be radical change on the council
over the next three years. Term limits will oust all other council members
except Joe Head and Mayor Susan Hammer by January 1995.;   Interviews with
council members and analysis of the year's voting record from council minutes
show these patterns:;   (check) Pandori, who represents downtown, lost more
council votes than any other member. But he won credit from some for sticking
to his principles. The year produced 38 split votes during open council
meetings. Twenty times Pandori was on the losing side; 10 of those were
solitary, quixotic no votes.;   (check) Shirakawa, elected from south and
central San Jose, is closely allied with 11-year council veteran Blanca
Alvarado and is most likely to diverge from the council majority on an issue
touching minority interests. He lost six votes.;   (check) Johnson,
representing the West Valley, styles herself an heir to Shirley Lewis and Judy
Stabile, two councilwomen who will leave office after 1992. On the losing side
only four times, Johnson is well liked and viewed as much more of an insider
than her predecessor, Lu Ryden.;   Of the three, Pandori probably made the
strongest impression in his first year. It seemed, from day to day, that
people either liked him or despised him, often for purely personal reasons.;
A former aide to ex-Mayor Tom McEnery, Pandori takes an aggressive, rational,
analytical approach to issues that strikes some people as annoying and aloof
and often costs him politically. Once he accused City Manager Les White of
driving "a loophole the size of the Caldecott Tunnel" through the council's
budget policy.;   Hammer said this about Pandori in June: "David is maturing
in how he deals with the council and city staff. That's going to serve him
well. He at first had a tendency to alienate people in the comments he would
make. I think he realizes that to be effective, you have to be a little more
circumspect about what you say in public.";   Five months later, as she was
redrawing the downtown district boundary against Pandori's wishes, Hammer
still sounded like a dean counseling a rambunctious schoolboy:;   "It may be
that from time to time he publicly sounds a little strident. We all go through
learning how to achieve what you achieve up here. Once you establish a
personal relationship, then you can be more effective on a professional
level.";   Still, Pandori got results, especially on downtown neighborhood
issues. His biggest victory was slowing expansion of San Jose International
Airport because of noise protests.;   The picture of Shirakawa and Johnson is
less clear. Both tend to let others lead debates.;   Shirakawa's strongest
stand came in April, when he opposed renaming the city's convention center
after McEnery. The vote was probably influenced by criticism minority groups
gave the former mayor during his second term.;   Shirakawa, who could not be
reached for this article, also pushed for affirmative action in city business
deals and devoted himself to schools relations and a 4,000-unit housing plan
for Communications Hill, in the center of his district.;   He was viewed as
genial and friendly, but also, at times, frustrated. "He was overwhelmed at
first," said Johnson. "I'm not sure he's enjoyed it. He's actually said so. I
asked, 'Are you having fun?' and he said, 'No, not really.' ";   Johnson seems
Shirakawa's mirror opposite, a government veteran who knows budget and
planning lingo, enjoys intercity diplomacy and environmental energy policy.
She, along with Pandori, voted against the general plan amendment that opens
92 acres in Edenvale to housing, a measure Shirakawa supported.;   Shirakawa
is burdened with several drug-plagued Project Crackdown neighborhoods.
Johnson's biggest district issue is street trees uprooting sidewalks. "It's
the thing I hear the most about, believe it or not," Johnson said. "Even more
than crime and traffic."; SAN JOSE'S CITY COUNCIL ROOKIE ROSTER; David
