<LEADPARA>  MAYOR Susan Hammer's redistricting plan is imperfect, like every other
redistricting plan proposed for San Jose so far. But it gets the city's
priorities right on some key issues, and it's the basis for a good map.;   The
redistricting committee mandated by the city charter drew a map last summer
that reduced the Hispanic concentration in District 3, the downtown, to under
50 percent. That would have left San Jose with only one Hispanic-majority
district -- an indefensible plan, which a review panel rejected.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  REDISTRICTING PROGRESS
NO MAP WILL PLEASE EVERYONE, BUT A GOOD COMPROMISE
IS NOW CLOSER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Under Hammer's map, District 3 is 55 percent Hispanic, and Asian-Americans
gain strength in Districts 4 and 8 -- although the map splits some heavily
Asian neighborhoods that other proposals kept intact.;   Uniting ethnic groups
often is accomplished at the expense of neighborhoods and school areas, and
some tinkering may be in order. For instance, Councilman David Pandori says
it's wrong to remove the Garden Alameda neighborhood from District 3.
Residents there are boiling mad about the new arena and ought to be able to be
in the downtown district. He claims the change would require little change in
the Hispanic percentage.;   Other areas may need another look as a result of
public reaction, which began at a meeting last night. But there is no way to
form districts that make everyone happy.;   The mayor's map is a big
improvement over most of the earlier proposals in one area: It keeps Alviso in
District 4 instead of moving it into District 3, where it would need to
compete for attention with time-consuming issues like the airport and downtown
redevelopment.;   Alviso would have been lost in District 3, and many of its
leaders knew that. It can be a much higher priority in District 4, which has
fewer high-profile problems.; FOLLOW-UP . . . The next public hearing on the
redistricting plan, followed by the council vote, will be 7 p.m. Dec. 3 at
city hall, 801 N. First St.  </TEXT>
