<DESCRIPT>  CITY; MANAGEMENT; OFFICIAL; CONTROVERSY; POLICE; EMPLOYMENT; SAN-JOSE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  If he didn't know already, City Manager Les White learned Monday how tough it
is to balance San Jose's budget at the expense of the city's men and women in
badges and blue.;    In its first public airing Monday morning, White's plan
to delay hiring nearly two dozen new officers next year to help close San
Jose's worst fiscal gap in a decade ran into a noncommittal mayor, a skeptical
city council and one councilman's flat accusation of a power grab.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHITE TAKES HEAT FOR PLAN TO STALL HIRING
OF COPS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Claiming that White's police cuts had skirted the council and mayor's
budget blueprint, Councilman David Pandori upbraided the manager with
surprisingly harsh language. Pandori charged that White was usurping key
policy tasks rightfully assumed by elected officials.;    "You're taking some
minor language in this proposal and building it into a loophole the size of
the Caldecott Tunnel," Pandori said. "I know you're squirming in your seat,
Les.";    In a sharp denial, White pounded the dais with his fist, insisting
that he was bringing his best professional judgment to the council. "If you
don't want the manager doing that," he said, "then what do you want the
manager doing on the budget?";    While none of Pandori's cohorts was quite so
scathing, several indicated they wanted the manager to serve up more budget
options -- options that would include something besides stretching out the
police hiring plan from five years to six.;    A few, however, supported
White, saying the police department should not be off-limits when the city
needs to close a $20 million deficit.;    "I don't think there is anything in
this budget that is so sacred that we can't at least discuss it," Councilwoman
Blanca Alvarado said.;    The so-called "police five-year plan" was born after
two officers died in a 1989 downtown shootout. Then-Mayor Tom McEnery agreed
to hire 45 officers a year through 1993 and the city's police union dropped a
lawsuit alleging a personnel shortage.;    This year, the force is budgeted
for more than 1,100 sworn officers. The rest of the five-year plan would bring
135 more officers on board.;    White proposes saving $1.4 million by pushing
back hiring dates. Next spring, 22 would be hired, then 90 in the following
two years, then the final 23 by 1994.;    White went beyond Mayor Susan
Hammer's March proposal for a simple three-month delay in hiring this year's
batch of 45 officers. Though she agrees with most of the rest of his budget,
Hammer has remained distant from White's police proposal, in what some
observers say is a political maneuver to make her own plan more palatable.;
Sgt. Mike Fehr, president of the Police Officers Association, said his group
would back Hammer's plan but not White's.;    Assistant Chief Fred Abram, in a
ticklish position because he is vying for the soon-to-be-vacant police chief's
post, said the police department needed to share budget pain with other
departments.;    "We're getting 22 new positions," Abram said. "That's more
than anyone else (in the city) is getting. That's a tough call on Les White's
part.";    White's "call" may become the budget's defining issue.;    Mike
Ferrero, business agent for the city's major employees union, the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, supports the budget as it
now stands. If White's judgment is overruled, Ferrero said, "it could upset
the delicate balance that's built into this budget."  </TEXT>
