<LEADPARA>  Testimony on Mayor Susan Hammer's proposed political map for San Jose's 10
city council districts on Tuesday night showed a widening rift between
Hispanic leaders, elated with the plan, and Asian leaders, upset that the
mayor didn't help them enough.;   Dozens of people from Alviso came, too, to
demand that the city pay more attention to problems in that long-neglected
bayside neighborhood. They demanded an Alviso master plan from the mayor, who
granted their wish to stay in the Berryessa district instead of moving to
downtown, as some had proposed.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HAMMER'S REMAP PLAN PLEASES HISPANICS, MIFFS ASIANS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The council, which considered the plan late into the night, is scheduled to
debate it again and vote Dec. 3.;   There was stark contrast between reactions
of the city's two leading ethnic groups.;   The Latino Issues Forum, the
Mexican-American Community Services Agency, La Raza lawyers and other Latino
groups streamed into the council chambers to congratulate the mayor, who in
her map released Monday significantly increased Hispanic power in two council
districts in central San Jose.;   "This is a plan for the 1990s," said voting
rights attorney Joaquin Avila. "It is a plan that can best provide access to
the political process for our Latino community.";   But Richard Konda,
representing the Asian-Pacific Islanders for Fair Reapportionment, said Hammer
should have been able to reach a 40 percent Asian concentration in the
Berryessa and Evergreen districts, instead of the 37 and 35 percent levels she
drew.;   And Lam Duc Nguyen, of the Indochinese Resettlement &amp; Cultural
Center, said: "I would like to share the joy of our Hispanic groups. But as an
Asian-American, I support Richard Konda's position.";   Other Asian leaders
argued that because the group accounted for much of the city's growth during
the 1980s, it should have been rewarded with more voting clout.;   Hammer said
Asian power was hard to achieve because Asian neighborhoods are generally more
dispersed than Hispanic neighborhoods.;   Some people came to defend their
neighborhoods, not their ethnicity. Some wanted to keep the College Park and
Garden Alameda areas, southwest of Stockton Avenue, in the downtown district,
instead of moving to the Willow Glen district as Hammer proposed. Some wanted
to keep traditional Berryessa areas from leaching into Alum Rock.;   Alex
Rubin, a College Park activist on noise issues surrounding San Jose
International Airport, gave the council a petition urging that the area remain
represented by downtown Councilman David Pandori.;   In other action Tuesday,
the council deferred acting on a proposed card-room tax.  </TEXT>
