<LEADPARA>  One San Jose councilman who voted last month for a controversial new housing
development in Edenvale now says he has changed his mind because of protests
raised by an elementary school district.;   But it's unclear whether the
switch by Councilman David Pandori will tilt the council against the Shea
Homes/Gibson Speno Co. proposal when it comes back to a vote Tuesday night.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EDENVALE PLAN LOSES BACKER ON S.J. COUNCIL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "This is an individual decision," said Pandori, who wants to study the
housing proposal next year side by side with other large planning issues. He
was one of eight ayes for the developers on Nov. 14. "I still fundamentally
agree that the city has to provide an equal amount of housing and jobs.";   As
it finishes another year of tinkering with San Jose's long-range planning, the
council will face at least two tough growth issues in South San Jose. The
Edenvale proposal could create up to 990 new homes on a vacant 92-acre parcel
east of Highway 101. And another potentially divisive proposal could bring 436
homes on 40 acres of an old golf course near Cottle Road and Santa Teresa
Boulevard.;   If those two are approved, it would mean that plans for 3,210
new housing units passed muster this fall. Those homes will help push San
Jose's population well beyond its estimated 1991 population of 791,645.;
Politicking on growth has been heavy in the past week, as developers make the
rounds of council members to lobby for votes, and developer foes, like
Councilwoman Judy Stabile, try to push the other way.;   Councilman Joe Head,
for instance, was spotted lunching on Wednesday with representatives of Gibson
Speno Co. at a restaurant near City Hall. Head had argued that the housing
will help drive industrial growth in South San Jose, but he was one of three
key council members -- the others were Pandori and Nancy Ianni -- who decided
last month to hear the complaints of the Oak Grove School District. Unless
those three had agreed to reopen the hearing, the deal would have been done.;
 Head, asked later about the meeting, described his vote as "very firm" in
favor of the developers, which is no surprise around City Hall. But he said he
had leaned on them to help Oak Grove schools. "I want to make sure they're
talking," Head said.;   The educators want $10 million for a school to handle
the children from the new neighborhood. But Hardy Childers, an assistant
superintendent, said Thursday, "We haven't gotten any answers yet." Other
alternatives, which Childers said are less palatable, include adding portable
classrooms to existing schools and long-distance busing.;   Another key issue
is fire service. Fire officials say the neighborhood would be seven to 11
minutes away from the closest firefighting response, well below the standard
service goal of four minutes.;   If a new station were built, city officials
say they would have a hard time funding the engine and truck companies to
staff it. Assistant Fire Chief Lee Suess said staffing alone would cost at
least $1 million and possibly up to $2.5 million a year, a large sum when the
city already faces a $20 million budget shortfall.;   However, Mayor Susan
Hammer and other City Hall sources say the proposal is still likely to pass,
even if the schools and fire issues remain up in the air. "I don't know if
everything's going to be worked out by Tuesday, but there have been some very
positive discussions," Hammer said.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; The city council
will meet at 7 p.m. Tuesday to vote on Edenvale and other general plan
amendments in the council chambers, 801 N. First St., San Jose.  </TEXT>
