<LEADPARA>  The San Jose City Council gave itself a 10 percent pay raise and Mayor Susan
Hammer an 11 percent raise Tuesday afternoon -- though the mayor and
Councilman David Pandori pledged their new dollars to favorite city programs
because of the city's tight budget.;    The 9-1 council vote, which followed
the advice of a citizen salary commission, locked salaries in place for two
years at $52,800 for the 10 council members and $80,000 for the mayor. The
raises take effect July 1.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. COUNCIL GIVES ITSELF A 10% RAISE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The council is in the midst of solving a $20 million budget shortfall. But
no one from the public spoke against the raises at the meeting.;    Council
members reasoned that the raises weren't outlandish, averaging roughly 5
percent a year. And they said flatly that they were worth it.;    Said Vice
Mayor Pat Sausedo: "The city is getting a bargain for what we're being paid. I
challenge anyone to look at my calendar.";    The council also discussed
proposing a ballot measure to pay the vice mayor more for the extra work that
comes with the job.;    Pandori voted against the raise. "My preference would
be to defer it for one year, given the city's present fiscal condition," he
said. Pandori said he will donate his $4,800 to needy city projects in his
district.;    Hammer said she will give her $8,000 to a new program called
"San Jose Best" that funnels money to schools for anti-gang and anti-drug
programs and curriculum enhancement.  </TEXT>
