<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; CITY; FINANCE; BUDGET; FORECAST; REPORT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  San Jose's number crunchers have handed Mayor Susan Hammer and the city
council a crushing report, pinpointing the city's projected deficit next year
at $20.6 million and predicting the financial picture will get worse in the
near future.;   "We're in the bottom of a pile of dung, fiscally," said Bob
Brownstein, Hammer's budget chief.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. FACES WORSENING FISCAL GAPS
NEW STUDY BLAMES SHRINKING REVENUES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     In a report released Friday, city budget director Larry Lisenbee blamed the
shortfall on slumping sales and property tax receipts and bulging expenses for
employee salaries, garbage service and police and fire staffing.;   The report
suggests that local government treasuries are often the best measure of how
well the economy is performing. Much more than trickling down, the national
recession has rained on City Hall. The upshot will undoubtedly mean tax
increases or deep service cuts next year -- maybe both.;   Five months after
Hammer trumpeted that she balanced a lousy budget with no layoffs or new
taxes, she may be facing both.;   In May, San Jose was eyeing a $10.3 million
budget shortfall for the 1993 fiscal year out of a general fund spending plan
of $419 million. That was before the retail market fell through the floor.
Estimates now show sales tax collections in San Jose down $7.2 million.;
"The May forecast assumed that an economic recovery would be well under way by
this point in time," Lisenbee wrote. "That clearly has not happened.";   A
year ago, Lisenbee calculated that the city could climb out of deficits within
five years, showing general-fund surpluses by 1995. Now he predicts nothing
but funding gaps through 1996.;   "This forecasted trend should concern us
more than the size of the deficit in any given year," Lisenbee wrote.;
Scenarios to climb out of the mess will emerge next week when the council
reviews the grim news and Hammer's plans to combat it.;   The plan, to be
released Tuesday, is still under wraps.;   However, Hammer has indicated she
expects to order a hiring freeze and favors a new gambling tax on card tables
at the Garden City club, as soon as possible.;   The city is studying several
other tax increases, including higher levies on cigarettes, car rentals,
out-of-state phone calls and entertainment tickets.;   Council members are
weighing in with other ideas.;   Councilwoman Blanca Alvarado wants to look at
higher fees on telephone, water and wastewater utilities, plus a steeper tax
on real estate sales. Councilwomen Shirley Lewis and Pat Sausedo would eye a
higher business tax on garbage dumps and charges to city-run enterprises.;
Other council members want to examine spending cuts and fee increases before
they look at taxes.;   On Friday, Councilman David Pandori brought up a wholly
different idea. Likening the city to a university, which should maintain
high-quality services no matter what the economy, Pandori proposed that the
city create its own endowment fund.;   By sloughing off $1 million in city
revenue each year and making high-rate, long-term investments, Pandori
calculated that San Jose could have an endowment worth $1 billion in 50 years.
Councilwoman Trixie Johnson has advanced a similar idea.;   But that notion
assumes the council has the political will to save those millions, instead of
spending as much as it can as soon as it can. Such will can be in short stock,
looking up through a dung heap.;   "Most funds like that start in a surplus
year," said Hammer's aide, Brownstein. "Very few people start them in a cut
year."  </TEXT>
