<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL; DANCE; RESTAURANT; LAW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  As downtown  San Jose becomes a more popular night spot, city officials
unfamiliar with overseeing a "24-hour city" have wrestled with defining what
type of night life they want.;    On Tuesday, the city council took the first
steps toward adopting a long-awaited ordinance, one that would allow
nightclubs throughout downtown, rather than creating a nightclub district.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MORE AREA FOR S.J.'S NIGHT LIFE
ALL OF DOWNTOWN CORE, NOT JUST ZONE, WEIGHED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "I think it's important that the city encourage and permit nightclub uses
throughout the downtown core," said Councilman David Pandori, who, along with
Mayor Susan Hammer, drafted a memo to the council that will become the basis
for the nightclub ordinance.;    The memo outlined four basic guidelines for
the future ordinance:;    (check) Nightclubs should be allowed throughout the
downtown core area. The policy that was proposed last year recommended
encouraging nightclubs in San Pedro Square, the Market Street area and the San
Antonio Plaza Redevelopment Area.;    (check) Rules regarding nightclubs
should be applied consistently to all areas downtown. The planning
commission's policy recommended excepting San Pedro Square from the guidelines
discouraging nightclubs from dominating certain streets. The memo stated that
San Pedro Square, like all areas downtown, should have a mixture of uses.;
(check) The new policy should apply to new nightclubs only. The redevelopment
agency had proposed applying the nightclub policy to existing as well as new
clubs.;    (check) Nightclubs will be discouraged from locating "adjacent to
or near residential areas." The planning commission's recommendation was that
the ordinance forbid nightclubs within 450 feet of residential areas. The memo
recommends "a more flexible guideline.";    The council has been criticized by
potential nightclub owners for not being receptive to clubs outside the
Pavilion Shops and other redevelopment areas. Last year, plans for two new
downtown clubs were thwarted. In one case -- the proposed Main Event club on
South First Street -- the controversy centered on its location across Gore
Park from an existing residential neighborhood and the future site of a
condominium project. Backers of the club eventually withdrew their plans.;
The council will also look at the possibility of letting clubs remain open,
but not serve alcohol, after 2 a.m., but that proposal was sent back to staff
for further evaluation. Also sent back for further study was a proposal to
establish an entertainment permit, which would be approved by the police
department.;    "These are all very sound recommendations," said Hammer. "I
think it's important that we diversify the nightclubs to other parts of the
downtown area. The Broadway area of San Francisco is exactly what we don't
want in San Jose."  </TEXT>
