<LEADPARA>  Faced with a roomful of downtown residents demanding that their neighborhood
parks be purged of crime and drugs, Councilman David Pandori last week
reaffirmed his support for a ranger program for the parks.;    Pandori also
announced that the city's Project Crackdown has been expanded into the area
around Roosevelt Park, considered the most troubled park in downtown.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PANDORI TAKES ON SAFETY IN PARKS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EX4/1, WL6  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Pandori said he and Mayor Susan Hammer have agreed on the funding in this
year's budget of at least one ranger for the downtown area and that he still
hopes to get more.;    The two programs come in response to longstanding
protests from residents who say the area's five parks -- Roosevelt, Backesto,
William Street, Ryland and St. James -- have become havens for gang activities
and drug dealing.;    Residents at the March 6 forum sponsored by People
Acting in Community Together (PACT) told of being approach by drug dealers,
seeing youths armed with weapons and fearing for their safety when at the
parks.;    "It's disappointing that I have to put (my daughter) into the car
and drive to a park because we can't enjoy our own park," one resident told
the roughly 100 people who attended the meeting. "I don't feel safe there.";
 Kay Lee, a PACT member, said she, too, has stopped visiting her neighborhood
park. "We used to go to Roosevelt Park because it was within walking
distance," she said. "But I always had to be aware of the surroundings and
didn't feel safe there.";    The forum on the status of the parks had been
planned weeks ago but took on a new sense of urgency when members of PACT
became concerned that San Jose's fiscal crisis might cause the ranger program
to be dropped from this year's city budget.;    At the meeting, PACT members
displayed large posters quoting Pandori's past support for the rangers program
when he was a candidate for the District 3 council seat in 1990. They also
posted charts showing that crime at the parks increased last year.;    Pandori
reassured the residents he was working to bring rangers to the downtown parks
and said he hoped that the program -- along with Project Crackdown -- will
make the parks safer for people to enjoy.;    "I will not vote for a budget in
the city of San Jose that does not have a pilot ranger program," he said.
"I've always had that commitment; I never lost that commitment.";    If the
program is approved, the unarmed rangers would work to keep the parks free of
crime and drug activity. Rangers are already used at larger citywide parks,
but their work there is largely limited to maintenance and youth programs.;
The program is attractive because it puts uniformed city officials in the
parks at a fraction of the salaries it would cost to pay police officers.;
One resident complained that having only one ranger to patrol the parks would
be insufficient, but Pandori said the proposal is a step in the right
direction. "It's a lot better than what we have now," he said.;    Pandori
insisted he said nothing to make PACT organizers believe he was not going to
support the rangers program.;    "We have completely different views on that,"
he said. "But we agree now.";    Project Crackdown involves getting residents
and several city agencies, including the police, together to coordinate
neighborhood activities, graffiti abatement and increased police protection.  </TEXT>
