<LEADPARA>  IN 1980, the Census found that Hispanics made up 22 percent of San Jose's
population. Today, according to the 1990 Census, the city is 30 percent
Hispanic.;   Given those numbers, you'd think the Latino Issues Forum would be
clamoring for more political clout, trying to expand Hispanics' voting power
when San Jose adjusts its city council district lines. Instead, it finds
itself fighting just to keep from losing ground.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ELIMINATING A HISPANIC MAJORITY DISTRICT IS WRONG  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Barbara Vroman is associate editor of the Mercury News editorial pages.
Commentary  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The redistricting committee's recommended map, known as the C map, cuts the
number of Hispanic-majority districts from two to one. It keeps a Hispanic
majority in District 5, the East Side, but it reduces the Hispanic percentage
in the downtown's District 3 from 52.6 percent to 48 percent.;   And because
of a rigid redistricting process, Hispanics have an uphill battle to keep
their voting strength in District 3.;   The Latino Issues Forum's attorney,
Joaquin Avila, cites voting rights laws and threatens to sue if the C map
isn't changed.;   Decisions should not be made solely to avoid a lawsuit. You
do what's right and defend the consequences. But to me, eliminating one of the
city's Hispanic majority districts just isn't right.;   It sends entirely the
wrong message. At a time when San Jose is supposed to be trying to bring more
minorities into government, this proposal says wait -- as soon as you get
close to having real voting power, we're going to notch you back a few pegs.;
 The redistricting committee, chaired by Richard Garcia, argues that the
current 53 percent majority of Hispanics in District 3 still isn't enough to
guarantee election of a Hispanic candidate, so cutting it a few points is
permissible. Pete Carrillo, president of the Latino Issues Forum, lost the
last council election in District 3 to David Pandori.;   But 10 years ago,
District 3 was only 45 percent Hispanic. The percentage has grown almost eight
points since then. At that rate, those neighborhoods would approach 60 percent
Hispanic by the end of this decade. District 5 is now 57 percent, and it sends
Blanca Alvarado to the city council.;   Setting District 3 Hispanics back five
points now makes it unlikely that they will approach 60 percent before the
next census. And what happens then? Will the next redistricting committee turn
the clock back as well?;   The current committee tried to balance the desire
of Hispanics and Asians to gain voting power with the wishes of neighborhoods
to remain united. Citywide, neighborhoods seem to have come out on top.;   Not
that neighborhoods are unimportant. At a hearing last week, Valerie Johnson
made an eloquent plea that her Warner Heights Homeowners Association stay in
District 8. Johnson says development in District 8 will affect Warner Heights,
and the association will have more clout if it's in the same district. She's
absolutely right.;   In fact, considering the issues city government deals
with, neighborhood power may be more important than ethnic-group power in most
cases. I'd hate to see San Jose dissolve into racial politics, pitting one
group against another.;   The thing about District 3, though, is that the C
map both disperses its Hispanic population and divides its neighborhoods. If
you apply the neighborhood test to draw a downtown district, it's easy to end
up with a majority of Hispanics.;   Besides, with all the alternative
proposals floating around, I believe there must be a way both to get District
3 back over 50 percent Hispanic, crossing that psychological threshold, and to
protect most neighborhoods. A few may be divided -- but then, a few in
District 3 that are now cut by the C map would be reunited. It won't be easy
to sway the city from that C map, though.;   A majority of the redistricting
committee defends it, even though everybody admits there wasn't enough time to
come up with alternatives. The review panel holding hearings on the plan will
listen to criticisms of the C map, but it won't talk about alternative
proposals. Framing the discussion that way rules out creative compromises.;
Ray Villareal and John Marshall Collins, both members of the redistricting
committee, continued trying to come up with alternatives after the deadline --
and found themselves villains in the eyes of the rest of the committee.;
Villareal originally helped draw the C map but later decided it did not do
enough to enhance minority voting power. Collins' goal was to find a better
plan for District 3's current neighborhoods, not to increase minority
concentrations.;   Ironically, Collins' map ends up giving District 3 the
highest Hispanic concentration of any current proposal -- 53.4 percent -- by
creating a compact, urban district.;   Villareal's map takes 3 just over 50
percent, and the Latino Issues Forum keeps it about where it is now, at 53
percent.;   Collins was named to the committee by Pandori, whose political
interests would be better served by the C map than by Collins': Pandori's main
appeal has not been to minorities. But he feels strongly that the downtown
neighborhoods should stay together -- placing him in an odd and unspoken
alliance with Pete Carrillo, the LIF president, who's likely to challenge him
again for the council seat.;   It's tempting to dismiss the LIF's protest as
an elect-Carrillo ploy, but that's too simplistic. The LIF has been making the
rounds of school boards, pushing them into district elections to give
Hispanics a better chance, and it was knee-deep in the county's redistricting
process. It would be in this fight even if Carrillo still lived in Morgan
Hill.;   Asian-Americans also are seeking greater power through redistricting.
They are just emerging as a political force, and they're likely to gain some
influence. At least, they don't stand to lose a majority district, as
Hispanics do.;   District 3 can and should remain a Hispanic-majority
district, and it can be done by grouping together related downtown
neighborhoods. The failure to make that happen will be a chilling sign not
only to Hispanics but to all minorities inching toward real power in San Jose.  </TEXT>
