<DESCRIPT>  MAYOR; SAN-JOSE; SUPPORT; LIFESTYLE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Mayor Susan Hammer and five San Jose City Council members were sworn into
office Monday in an early evening ceremony that drew almost 1,200 well-wishers
to the city's Convention Center.;    In a three-minute speech, Hammer
reiterated her pledge to "embrace the diversity of San Jose."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HAMMER HAILS S.J. DIVERSITY
CITES STRENGTH IN DIFFERENCES AS SHE, 5 OTHERS
TAKE OFFICE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "We rejoice in our differences and recognize them as our strengths," she
said, "because in the end the legacy of how we dealt with one another will be
far more important than any structure we build or any program we implement.";
  Hammer seemed to be attempting to differentiate herself from her
predecessor, Tom McEnery, who squabbled with the Hispanic community over
various downtown building plans.;    "We begin tonight a new era in San Jose's
history," Hammer said. "Juntos si podemos. Together we can do it.";    Among
those who applauded Hammer's brief speech were McEnery, San Francisco Mayor
Art Agnos, and Santa Clara County supervisors Rod Diridon and Ron Gonzales.
U.S. Rep. Don Edwards, D-San Jose, was to have introduced Hammer, but his
flight was delayed by bad weather. Gonzales substituted for him.;    Despite
the speechmaking and the catered reception that followed, Monday's ceremony
was strictly pro forma. Hammer and the others, who took office Jan. 1 under
city law, all were sworn in earlier at a series of private ceremonies in
December.;    Hammer, 52, was sworn in Dec. 26 by Superior Court Judge John
Flaherty, a longtime family friend, who again administered the oath Monday.
The gathering, held in the mayor's office, was attended by Hammer's husband,
parents and children.;    Other council members, including the three newly
elected representatives, repeated their oaths individually in front of City
Clerk Andrea Membreno.;    "We already had the circumstance, this is the
pomp," joked Andrea Leiderman, aide to council veteran Jim Beall, who is
beginning his last four-year term.;    It won't be the last of that pomp. The
mayor's Unity Breakfast, a tradition started eight years ago by McEnery, is
scheduled for Jan. 23. It is there that Hammer will deliver her first State of
the City speech.;    Monday's inauguration was put together to give the
politicians' supporters and city residents a chance to celebrate publicly,
said Gary Robinson, Hammer's chief of staff.;    "It seemed like a good way to
kick into a new administration . . . with a lot less than a full-blown gala,"
Robinson said. "I think people are pleased and believe it's a good way for the
new administration to begin. We haven't heard a word of criticism.";
Robinson and his staff had expected about 750 to attend the event, but by
early Monday afternoon more than 1,000 people had said they would be there.;
 Although Hammer's staff sent out about 2,000 invitations, the ceremony and
reception were open to everyone at no charge.;    The catered reception that
followed the mayor's brief speech and the oaths featured cheese, fruit,
vegetables, egg rolls, wine and Calistoga water.;    The $10,000 price tag
will be paid mostly from a part of the mayor's budget that was set aside for
the transition, said Robinson. Any cost overrun will most likely be paid from
money in Hammer's "Friends Committee" campaign account, he said.;    In
addition to Hammer and Beall, who represents District 9, the other newly
sworn-in council members are veteran Blanca Alvarado from District 5 and
newcomers Trixie Johnson from District 1, David Pandori from District 3, and
George Shirakawa from District 7.  </TEXT>
