<LEADPARA>  Though veterans wanted a war memorial, and many Hispanics liked the name just
the way it was, in the end the San Jose City Council chose Tuesday to insert
the moniker McEnery squarely into the title of the San Jose Convention
Center.;    The center, an anchor of the city's rebuilt core since it opened
in April 1989, will now be the San Jose McEnery Convention Center.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. COUNCIL PAYS TRIBUTE TO MCENERY
EX-MAYOR'S NAME ADDED TO CONVENTION CENTER
TITLE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     An 8-3 council majority paid tribute to Tom McEnery, the city's 61st mayor,
by renaming the edifice for the man it called a seminal downtown visionary.
McEnery ended eight years as San Jose mayor in December.;    "A lot of people
participated in making this city what it is today, but only one person led,"
said Councilwoman Shirley Lewis, who voted for the name change with Mayor
Susan Hammer and council members Joe Head, David Pandori, Pat Sausedo, Trixie
Johnson, Nancy Ianni and Judy Stabile.;    Council members George Shirakawa,
Jim Beall and Blanca Alvarado dissented.;    Other opponents were members of
the Korean War Veterans Association, the American G.I. Forum, and the Veterans
of Foreign Wars, who touted a "San Jose Memorial Convention Center." Said Mike
Borquez, commander of VFW Post 344: "You should start by memorializing the
many, instead of the few.";    Several Hispanic representatives were also
passionate opponents, including Al Rodriguez, the owner of KAZA-AM 1290, a
Spanish-speaking radio station, and Sofia Mendoza, a community activist.;
"Name the street he lives on McEnery Street, and put the Fallon statue in his
front yard," said Mendoza, alluding to the controversy over city pioneer
Thomas Fallon that tainted McEnery in the eyes of many Hispanics.;    But
there was plenty of testimony in McEnery's favor.;    The San Jose Juniors
showed up 40-strong to vouch for McEnery, who has supported the 2-year-old
teen-age volleyball club since it began two years ago. "Mayor McEnery deserves
the recognition for all the things he's done with youth," said Emely Bigge,
17, a senior at Independence High.;    In other issues, the council designated
the Jose Theater a city landmark and hiked residential garbage collection
rates from $7.59 per household to $9.80 per month, effective July 1.  </TEXT>
