<LEADPARA>  THE SAN JOSE City Council has delivered a body check to local culture by
deciding that Pamela and Bill Resch cannot hold salon-style piano recitals in
their home.;   This is the couple, you may remember, who were busted last
summer after two undercover San Jose vice squad officers attended a recital at
which Pamela Resch performed works by Beethoven, Chopin and Liszt.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A SOUR NOTE FOR S.J. CULTURE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     This is the same vice squad, you may also remember, that gets naked and
goes to any length to bust suspected prostitutes.;   Anyway, the recital issue
came down to whether the Resches were running an illegal business. For seven
years, they've performed salon-style concerts in their storybook cottage in
San Jose's Naglee Park neighborhood and charged admission -- $25 per guest.;
This included a glass of wine along with a piano recital by Pamela Resch, who
has played concert halls in New York, London and Vienna.;   Until the
Beethoven bust last summer, the only charge against her had been a 1980 New
York Times review saying she'd been "too unbridled" with a Bach piece in
Carnegie Hall.;   BUT LAST summer, the state Alcoholic Beverage Control office
called to remind the Resches that they couldn't serve wine without a state
liquor license. They stopped.;   But a police investigation continued. The
officers turned up evidence that the Resches lacked a business license. Their
house was not zoned for commercial (concert) use. They owed back business
taxes. They owed penalty payments in addition to back business taxes.;   They
started the recitals to recapture the 19th-century world of classical music,
when there were no great concert halls and so Beethoven and Chopin and Haydn
performed in patrons' homes.;   The question before the city council Tuesday
night was whether that was an appropriate activity for a 1990s San Jose home.;
  Councilman David Pandori, whose district includes the Naglee Park
neighborhood, proposed designating the Resches as artists in residence and
giving them a conditional permit to resume their concerts.;   "Allowing these
concerts can enhance the quality and uniqueness of our city," he said.;   The
proposal was narrowly drawn to limit sound, audience size and parking, and to
prohibit booze -- restrictions the Resches agreed with. But it also opened the
way to designate other artists in residence in other downtown neighborhoods.;
 Seemed like a neat idea for a city whose current cultural notoriety comes
from landing the Sharks, a National Hockey League franchise.;   MORE THAN 100
concertgoers wrote letters of support. More than 40 supporters showed up
Tuesday night. Neighbors even signed a petition saying they had no problems
with noise or traffic.;   Pandori, joined by Mayor Susan Hammer and council
members Jim Beall and Nancy Ianni, voted for the ordinance. Seven turned it
down.;   Their problems ranged from deciding who is an artist in residence to
discriminating against neighborhoods outside the downtown area to law
enforcement.;   "So they voted against us, but they let people hold Tupperware
parties in their homes and hold garage sales without having business
licenses," Bill Resch said Wednesday morning as he prepared to cancel the
couple's annual Christmas Bach celebration.;   In fairness, it should be noted
that Mayor Hammer and several council members, including several who voted
against their home concerts, told the Resches they would help them find a more
public facility.;   But you've got to wonder, the way things have gone, just
what they might have in mind.;   The Cow Palace maybe? Between periods, while
they sweep the ice at the Sharks games?  </TEXT>
