<DESCRIPT>  ANALYSIS; SAN-JOSE; CITY; MANAGEMENT; GOVERNMENT; OFFICIAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  As City Manager Les White mulls a dozen police chief candidates and carves a
leading role for his office in the city's pursuit of a new baseball stadium,
he shows convincing proof that a council-appointed manager still can drive San
Jose government.;   The departure of Tom McEnery from the mayor's office in
December gave White a chance to co-opt power on two fronts: New Mayor Susan
Hammer had to prove she could fill McEnery's shoes, and Redevelopment Agency
Executive Director Frank Taylor, White's peer and sometime rival, lost his
most potent patron.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CITY MANAGER EMERGES AS POWER IN SAN JOSE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Analysis  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Ten months later, as the power vacuum gives way to power-sharing, White has
emerged as a catalytic force in a consensus-driven, coalition form of
government. At the same time, White and city council members say Hammer shows
all signs of assuming the strong-mayor role McEnery bequeathed her.;   At
Hammer's lead, doors are open everywhere in City Hall. Hammer meets with
White. Hammer meets with Taylor. Hammer meets with White and Taylor. White and
Taylor are seen on long tete-a-tete walks. All three meet one-on-one,
regularly, with city council members.;   Leslie Robert White, 51, a native of
Dinuba, a Tulare County farm town, was named city manager in May 1989. A
6-foot bear of a man with a salt-and-pepper beard and an occasionally volcanic
temper, White has an activist view of his role in government.;   Asked to
comment on his power, he said, half in jest, "Like most city managers, I feel
there's never enough of it.";   At times, White chafes at the city charter
checks and balances that dilute his authority, such as the council's veto
power over his department head appointments. But he admits, "I have to be a
realist and deal with the cards that have been dealt.";   This year White has
built his coalitions quietly, increasing his influence without upstaging the
mayor or the council.;   Consider the case of the ballpark. While the mayor
takes credit for the initiative to lure the San Francisco Giants, White has
put two of his deputies, Darrell Dearborn and D. Kent Dewell, squarely in the
middle of the stadium team.;   Straightforward stuff, on its face. Because
taxes may be raised to pay for the stadium, White has a legitimate claim on
the project.;   But the redevelopment agency -- an arm of government outside
White's domain -- has budgeted $40 million for the stadium and is paying the
lion's share now for consultants that White and his deputies will help manage.
The stadium site, near Highway 237 and Zanker Road, is in a redevelopment
area, but last spring, Hammer said she had to twist Taylor's arm to get him to
support the stadium.;   And when two council reports were produced last month
for the stadium initiative -- one by Hammer, working with White's staff, and
one by Taylor's staff -- Hammer called the agency memo "totally misleading."
It put forward a long-term cost -- $860,000 -- that was at odds with the
$640,000 sum the mayor had used at her news conference days earlier.;   This
all adds up to a large role for White, and a peripheral role for Taylor, in
what Hammer calls San Jose's "biggest project ever.";   "The agency's role is
much more limited on the Giants," Hammer aide Bob Brownstein said. "It's
essentially a city project. Frank is basically a downtown-oriented
redevelopment director. He didn't cede authority (because) he never competed
for authority.";   Then there is the police chief selection, a choice White
will make this month. His pick to succeed Joe McNamara could put a lasting
mark on the city, perhaps outliving White's own term in office.;   As with the
stadium effort, White has asserted his authority while consulting the mayor
and the council and spreading the credit around. He held a public forum in
May. He sought council help in crafting interview questions. Then, last
weekend, he closed up shop, sequestering his staff and the 12 semifinalists in
a hotel while he led the grill sessions.;   The choice, he said, is his to
make. The council won't challenge him.;   Rookie Councilman David Pandori, who
earlier this year accused White of grabbing power, now speaks of him as a team
player.;   "The administration works through the mayor's office," Pandori
said. "Whether it's on the budget, whether it's on the Giants, on any issue,
they coordinate with the mayor. That practice has been ingrained here in the
city.";   Pandori's comments underscore White's most effective trait: to be
everywhere behind the scenes, and nowhere stealing the show.;   White's
influence is so well-hidden that an elementary civics lesson can seem
startling. In the city charter, Article III says simply: "The municipal
government established by this charter shall be known as the Council-Manager
form of government." Nowhere does it mention the mayor.;   Councilman Joe
Head, an advocate of the strong-mayor government and no stranger to power
himself, said: "The manager is a very powerful position, and Les is a very
powerful person, no question about that. . . . The importance of the manager
is now getting some focus. He's getting a chance to make some sexy decisions."  </TEXT>
