<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; POLICE; OFFICIAL; EMPLOYMENT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The last time San Jose hired a police chief, there was no community forum, no
head-hunting search firm, no city council politics.;    Instead, there was
just then-City Manager Ted Tedesco, who simply went out and found somebody he
liked: Joseph McNamara.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J.'S HIGH-CALIBER SEARCH FOR TOP COP
EXTENSIVE SELECTION PROCESS DRAWS SCRUTINY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But times have changed since Tedesco's 1976 solo search. Community groups
want a role in selecting the next chief. Council members can veto City Manager
Les White's nominee.;    Choosing McNamara's successor is arguably White's
most important decision since he himself was appointed two years ago. It is
doubly sensitive in a city with no ethnic majority and a new mayor actively
crusading against drugs and gangs -- and for "diversity.";    Members of the
Hispanic community tout two local candidates, Hispanic-American deputy chiefs
Lou Cobarruviaz and Luis Hernandez. "This is a historic opportunity," said
Victor Garza, president of the local American GI Forum, a Hispanic-American
veterans group.;    The decision is White's, unless the council vetoes his
choice. Council members -- and Mayor Susan Hammer -- say they will have only
indirect influence on White's nomination.;    But sensing the political mine
fields, White has installed a methodical, cautious -- and widely praised --
hiring plan. It includes a public brainstorming session on the ideal new
chief, held last month; a national talent search, under way soon; and a
battery of interviews and background checks before the chief is hired in late
summer or early fall.;    For now, White is casting a broad net. He wants
candidates from inside and outside the city, women and minority members, and
those with "sensitivity to the interests and needs of a diverse population.";
  Once White gets a field of 15 or so from San Francisco-based head-hunting
firm Slavin Nevin and Associates, he'll put each through the paces:;
(check) Grilling by a pair of five-member panels composed of people from
community groups and professionals in government and law enforcement.;
(check) Back-to-back one-on-one meetings with White and Assistant City Manager
Regina V.K. Williams, who oversees the police department and has hired police
chiefs in Richmond, Va., and Ypsilanti, Mich. Williams has already influenced
this hiring round; the May forum, a San Jose first, was modeled after one she
held in Richmond.;    (check) A lengthy psychological exam.;    (check) A
meeting with some top city officials, including Fire Chief Robert Osby.;
White will then pick three or four finalists, keeping the names secret from
almost everyone, except Hammer.;    Then the fun starts.;    While reporters,
city officials and police try to uncover the short list, White will discreetly
check references. If a candidate is from out of town, White, Williams or a key
subordinate will take an unannounced field trip to gauge that community's
sentiments. How the potential chief fares in his hometown paper is crucial.;
 Decision time;    By late summer or early fall, White will reveal his choice
to the city council. Hammer will meet the nominee before White lets the
council interview the candidate. A 1986 city charter amendment granted the
council the power of advice and consent whenever the manager appoints a
department head.;    It's similar to how the Senate reviews presidential
nominees but with key differences: Interviews are done in closed session, and
so far no one has been rejected. Since 1986, the council has approved several
city directors, but this will be the first fire or police chief nominee
grilled.;    Before the grilling starts, the council will help shape the
questions White asks his short list candidates, but its influence on the final
choice will come sparingly, if at all.;    Little lobbying so far;
Councilwoman Blanca Alvarado said she has already rejected some in her
district who want her to lobby for a minority member. "I don't intend to do
anything," she said. "I have to rely on the city manager's judgment.";
Hammer and her staff are also giving White leeway. "It's the manager's
prerogative to bring forth one candidate," the mayor said.;    In interviews
with elected officials, only Councilman David Pandori floated a challenge to
White's authority. "It would be interesting to come up with a short list
rather than just one name," he said, allowing that White had the right to make
the final nomination.;    "I'd be very interested in having the ability to
question a short list of candidates.";    Asked if he would consider Pandori's
idea, White said: "No. You can't get too many people involved in managing the
city. Next question.";    So far, lobbying from community groups has been
limited largely to the May forum, which drew praise for McNamara and hopes
that the new chief would be just as progressive. It also won White kudos from
minorities and the council. "Les seemed to hear us," said Paul Wysocki, a
political activist for gays and lesbians.;    One intriguing plug has come
from Ronald L. Havner, who oversees the city's police academy at Evergreen
Valley College. Havner wrote White on behalf of Deputy Chief Cobarruviaz. As
the summer winds on, similar testimonials for the city's other top cops --
Acting Chief Fred Abram, deputy chiefs Tom Frazier, Bill Mallett and Hernandez
-- are likely to pour into city hall.;    White said he will listen to
everyone equally. "I don't run this place like a monarchy or some fiefdom.";
 White unlike predecessor;  He stands in contrast to former City Manager
Tedesco -- now an American Airlines executive in Dallas -- who in May 1976
fired former Chief Robert Murphy without consulting council members, saying
the chief had lost control of a police force that was "overly aggressive.";
"If I was going to take responsibility for firing Murphy, then I was going to
take the responsibility for finding a replacement," said Tedesco, who served
from 1973 to 1978. " . . . I viewed it as my choice and my decision.";
Tedesco did not advertise for candidates. "My assumption was the best people
are not out there . . . applying for a job.";    Nor did he hire a search
firm. "Suppose they don't come up with the right ones? Then you've to send
them back (out).";    Instead, he phoned chiefs at 25 large cities and asked
them who they considered the top five or six police chiefs in America.
"Interestingly enough," Tedesco said, "the same names kept coming up.";    He
called them up and encouraged them to apply -- including Kansas City chief,
Joe McNamara.;    In August 1976, Tedesco announced the hiring of McNamara,
who raised officers' standards and improved race relations. When McNamara
retired last month, many hailed him as the nation's finest police chief.;
Tedesco criticized White's forum, which let citizens voice what qualities they
wanted in a chief, saying it accomplishes little and abrogates the manager's
responsibility. "You democratize the thing to the point of absurdity," he
said.;    But Tedesco fully realizes that his method has gone the way of the
dinosaur. "I can't give Les any advice," Tedesco said. "He is a city manager
in a different time."  </TEXT>
