<DESCRIPT>  LETTER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Last Tuesday evening I attended a downtown theatrical performance which was
very avant-garde in its concepts. The minor players had all the best lines and
the star of the show, a well established actress, let down her mask and gave
us all a glimpse at the private side of a very public person.;   I really
believe the producers of the show deserve top billing in the discredits. They
staged the show carefully. They funded many of the players and pulled off a
coup by duping many of the performers into believing they were their parts.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SAN JOSE'S LEADING LADY LET HER MASK SLIP A BIT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Letters to the Editor  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The theater? The San Jose City Council chambers. The star? Mayor Susan
Hammer. The players? The unemployed and the Oak Grove School District. The
producer? The developers behind the Levin General Plan Amendment in the
Edenvale area. The remaining cast? Excluding the six council members who voted
with Mayor Hammer for reconsideration, the rest of us were and remain . . .
victims.;   Let's get to the plot. San Jose has a general plan. The city
planner understands it, police officers and firefighters understand it, the
head of parks and recreation understands it, the school board understands it.
Most everyone understands it -- except developers and friends. Mayor Hammer
either doesn't understand it, or chooses to ignore it, as she does when
various heads of city departments attempt to clarify the situation for her.;
OK, now to the nitty-gritty. 600-900 new houses to be built on a piece of land
designated industrial. It's called affordable housing. Houses between $200,000
to $300,000 (as I said, affordable housing). A piece of land, designated
industrial, unequipped to deal with educational needs, police and fire
protection requirements or the inherent traffic implications. None of these
were satisfactorily addressed in the environmental impact report. All of the
aforementioned services have been stretched to their limits.;   It would have
been very easy to know at whom to boo and hiss and whom to applaud, if it
weren't for the unemployment problem. My heart hurt. These were mothers and
fathers, friends and neighbors begging for a chance to work. I want them to
work. I want to tell them it will be better.;   The Levin Plan Amendment is
not the answer. It is a short-term solution to a long-term problem that will,
in fact, greatly exacerbate this problem. I understand their fears, as do the
developers. Empathizing and playing on the fears and weaknesses of others were
the bases for the antithetical arguments given at the meeting. As I stood
waiting for my turn at the podium and a chance to speak, I realized Mayor
Hammer greeted her friends on a first-name basis, and all her friends were
pro-developers.;   I am outraged. Councilman David Pandori earned high marks
for his efforts, as did the other three council members who voted against the
mayor and endured despite her condescending attitude toward them. They fought
for what is right and I hope we all will continue to do just that. Recall
Mayor Hammer. We need someone who takes our lives as seriously as she takes
her own name.;   -- Yvonne Rafi;   San Jose  </TEXT>
