<DESCRIPT>  EDITORIAL; SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL; POLICY; HOUSING; DEVELOPMENT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ARE a few hundred new houses worth the cost of abandoning San Jose's
principles of prudent planning for growth?;   No. But some city council
members seem ready to approve housing in the middle of open land in Edenvale,
pure urban sprawl, because they think it will attract industry.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WRONG HOUSING IDEA
MORE REASONS WHY SAN JOSE CITY COUNCIL SHOULD
REJECT THE EDENVALE PROJECT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     They're going by anecdotal evidence, much of it passed on by the developers
who want to build the housing -- Shea Homes and Gibson Speno. Yet the city's
professional staff is convinced this plan is bad: It will drain services from
existing neighborhoods, and it may even harm efforts to market redevelopment
land.;   San Jose got to be the way it is -- sprawling, often impossible to
serve with mass transit -- because of just this sort of growth: approved
because developers asked, not because of good planning.;   The city tried to
change that in recent years. But now Mayor Susan Hammer is sending a different
signal.;   She's not the only one changing direction. Councilwoman Pat Sausedo
had opposed a 1988 housing plan in Edenvale industrial land because, according
to council minutes, "the council needs to look at the economic plan
comprehensively, not on a piecemeal basis." Yet now she's the head cheerleader
for this far more damaging project.;   More surprising is the change by Joe
Head, who two years ago opposed a similar plan because, again according to
minutes, "any major general plan change must be plan-centered, not
site-centered." He says he changed his mind because he's impatient with the
city's slowness in finding room for more single family homes.;   But that's an
argument to speed up planning studies, not to toss the principles out the
window.;   The lack of planning eventually struck Councilman David Pandori,
who at first supported this year's Edenvale proposal. He now says he will vote
to study the site further, joining the three original opponents of the plan in
their effort to seek a compromise with the mayor.;   George Shirakawa and
Blanca Alvarado should join them as well: Both represent low-income
neighborhoods that need more police protection and code enforcement, not less.
This housing will drain those services from their areas.;   The council made a
bad decision last month, but that can be reversed Tuesday, when the hearing on
the plan is reopened.;   Hammer prides herself on action, not study. But there
is no honor in action that disregards the best interests of the city. The
council should study how best to use Edenvale land and then -- only then --
consider proposals to develop it.; FOLLOW-UP . . . The hearing will be 7 p.m.
Tuesday at city hall, 801 N. First St., San Jose.  </TEXT>
