<DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; REAL-ESTATE; DEVELOPMENT; SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL; MEETING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  While Mayor Susan Hammer keeps mum on her most significant development vote
since taking office, two of California's home-building giants have forged an
alliance to persuade the city to open up a large South San Jose tract for
housing.;   The city council will vote tonight on whether to convert 92 acres
of industrial land in Edenvale to a cluster of up to 990 homes, developed by
Shea Homes, the Gibson Speno Co. and Kaufman &amp; Broad South Bay Inc. All three
helped bankroll Hammer's 1990 mayoral campaign.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOME BUILDER ALLIANCE TO TEST CITY'S RESOLVE
EDENVALE PROPOSAL CALLS FOR UP TO 990 DWELLINGS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The developers face a very close vote, though some City Hall nose counters
predict they'll win in a 7-4 roll call, with Hammer's backing.;   Kaufman &amp;
Broad joined forces about a month ago to build the homes with Shea. The
newcomer's arrival has political resonance around City Hall because Hammer
cast a swing vote exactly three years ago to allow a nearby Kaufman &amp; Broad
development, over the strenuous complaint of then-Mayor Tom McEnery.;   The
Edenvale parcel, owned by Monterey Highway businessman Richard Levin, is now a
grazing field tucked between Highway 101 and the Diablo Range, just north of
Coyote Valley. For eight years, city officials have viewed it as a site for an
industrial campus, one piece of a hoped-for economic engine called "Silicon
Valley South.";   The plan aimed to build jobs on the city's southern fringe
before housing, in a bid to ease freeway congestion and lay away prime land
for San Jose's tax base.;   Shea Homes -- builder of the huge Silver Creek and
River Oaks projects in Evergreen and north San Jose -- and Gibson Speno --
supplier of capital and political know-how -- applied in March for an
exception to that policy. They argued that jobs won't come unless housing is
built first.;   The application is coming to a head with the city's annual
general plan hearings.;   Hammer, who met with the developers a week ago,
won't say how she's leaning. Vice Mayor Pat Sausedo, whose district
encompasses the parcel, wouldn't return phone calls. Council members Nancy
Ianni, George Shirakawa and Blanca Alvarado say they're undecided. Jim Beall
is leaning toward the project. David Pandori and Joe Head say they're for it.
Judy Stabile, Trixie Johnson and Shirley Lewis say they're against it.;
Hammer, who apparently has not lobbied the council on the amendment, said
Wednesday afternoon the media has "blown the issue out of proportion.";   But
Lewis said the developers "see a window of opportunity here with the new
leadership, and I think they're testing that. I don't think the council will
fold on this.";   On Nov. 14, 1988, when Kaufman &amp; Broad brought a similar
issue to the council, Hammer, Ianni and Beall voted for it in the majority,
while Sausedo, Alvarado, Lewis and Stabile voted no.;   That 500-unit project,
known as California Maison, now sits just west of the Levin property, at
Monterey Highway and Bernal Road. It sells about eight units a week, starting
at $150,000 -- "the fastest-selling community in Northern California," boasted
Roger Menard, Kaufman &amp; Broad's South Bay president.; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED;
The city council will meet at 7 p.m. tonight to discuss the general plan in
the council chambers at 801 N. First St.  </TEXT>
