<LEADPARA>  THE convenience and economic benefits of having an airport downtown are not
without cost.;    But in deciding the future of San Jose International
Airport, the city council needs to keep in mind that the benefits far outweigh
the drawbacks.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE SOUND OF GROWTH
NEGOTIATE NOISE CONTROLS; BUT REMEMBER, CLEARLY
THE AIRPORT MUST EXPAND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     For the past several months, city officials have been listening to
complaints from people who live near the airport and fear that a proposed
master plan for expansion will make their neighborhoods unlivable.;    The
proposal would triple the number of passengers using the airport to 21.2
million per year by 2010. It would increase the number of flights coming and
going per hour from 18 to 44.;    Meanwhile, American Airlines can't fill up
its flights to Tokyo because the planes would be too heavy to take off on San
Jose's short runways. And on two occasions, the Tokyo flight had to make a
fueling stop in Oakland because a full tank would have kept it grounded here.;
   That's ridiculous. Clearly the airport must grow. Runways must be long
enough to handle overseas flights, and the growth of population and business
in Silicon Valley demands better overall service.;    Councilman David
Pandori, who represents neighborhoods near the airport, worries that it's
growing for the sake of growth, with too little attention to specific needs
and too little concern for noise and other problems. He wants further study of
those issues. That's fair.;    Mayor Susan Hammer also says the proposed plan
needs more study and, like Pandori, believes noise controls and curfews should
eventually be part of city law. That's fair too, as long as the rules are
negotiated with the airlines first to make certain they're reasonable.;    The
city takes a measured approach to planning for land development; it doesn't
fill up every open space with the maximum density. Airport growth should be
planned the same way. Before approving the master plan, council members must
