<LEADPARA>  Two years after losing a bitter battle to add fast-moving Asian tile wagering
in its San Jose poker club, Garden City on Tuesday handily won its latest
high-stakes gamble with the San Jose City Council.;    The council finally
approved the club's request to substitute the so-called Asian games -- super
pan nine and double-handed poker -- for panguingue, known as pan.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. CARD CLUB WINS OK FOR TWO NEW GAMES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Michelle Guido contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Double-handed poker is almost identical to pai gow, a Chinese tile game
that the council rejected two years ago. Then, however, the council did
approve substituting Texas hold-em for straight poker.;    Mayor Susan Hammer
said after the meeting that she may present her proposal for raising gambling
taxes or fees later this week. Garden City already pays more than $250,000 a
year in fees, but other cities that allow gambling charge much more.;
Hammer contends that the fee proposal is not related to permission to change
games but is simply a way of whittling down the city's projected $24 million
budget deficit.;    Despite the possibility of higher fees, the 8-3 vote was a
major victory for the club's owners, the Dalis family.;    "It lets us stay
competitive with other card clubs in the area," said Nicholas J. Dalis, a
former club president.;    Favors fewer restrictions;  The council vote was
not the only good news for Dalis and his family, which owns the 40-table club,
the largest in Northern California. Councilwoman Shirley Lewis hinted that she
thinks the club should be allowed to offer any game that's legal in the
state.;    "I don't think there's any other business in town that has to go
through this kind of thing," Lewis said.;    Police, who argue that poker
clubs are magnets for crime, groaned at the prospect.;    Tuesday's revision
drew strong opposition from the police department, on paper at least. The
council made it clear that it didn't want to listen to police crime statistics
and other arguments again.;    The only vocal opposition came from a woman who
said her husband is undergoing therapy for a gambling problem.;    "I don't
know how you can allow more games when it should be closed down," Nidia
Fonseca Hanson said. "My husband has been approached by bookies, solicited by
prostitutes while playing there. . . . The problem is, you don't know what
it's like to be called by bookies threatening to throw acid in your face if
you don't pay them thousands of dollars.";    Hammer noted that the club is
legally licensed and was not seeking an increase in tables, total number of
games or betting limits. She said a request to substitute games is a
legitimate way to "keep up with changing demographics of this city.";
'Asian games';    Super pan nine and double-handed poker are known as "Asian
games" because they originated in China and are tremendously popular among
Chinese and Vietnamese. The games are fast-paced and high-stakes, with
thousands of dollars changing hands within minutes, police say.;    Hanson
persisted, referring to the Dalises' pending trial in Superior Court on
conspiracy and tax charges stemming from an alleged multimillion-dollar
profit-skimming operation said to have been run by Nick Dalis, and to
additional charges that club owners tried to expand their political power by
arranging illegal campaign contributions.;    "Doesn't that cast aspersions on
their honesty?" she asked.;    Hammer retorted, "One of the things I like
about this country is, people are innocent until proven guilty.";    But
Councilwoman Trixie Johnson, who was criticized during her campaign last year
for accepting Garden City donations, said she would rather not vote for game
changes "until after the legal clouds have cleared." She was joined in her
opposition by David Pandori, who did not take donations from the club, and
Nancy Ianni.;    Majority backs Hammer;  The rest of the council members
supported Hammer. They included George Shirakawa, who said he has played cards
at the club for more than two decades.;    In other action Tuesday:;
(check) The council unanimously approved Councilwoman Blanca Alvarado's
proposal to give residents a new conduit for police misconduct complaints.
Under her plan, a deputy city manager will be designated as "community
relations liaison" to receive and track the complaints.;    Alvarado's plan
also asks the city attorney's office to look at the legality of existing
procedures for public disclosure of the number, types and disposition of
misconduct charges filed against officers.;    (check) The council took the
first step toward redrawing the city's 10 council districts, based on the 1990
census. On a unanimous vote, the council approved Hammer's plan to appoint a
committee to set redistricting guidelines so that another appointed group can
get to work immediately when detailed census figures are released.  </TEXT>
