<LEADPARA>  A group of parking lot owners wants the city of San Jose to put the brakes on
a plan to prop up downtown commerce by expanding free and city-subsidized
parking.;    Among the biggest losers under the new plan are owners of private
lots near the city-owned Market Street Garage, including former Mayor Tom
McEnery's family, owners of a surface lot across San Pedro Street.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PARKING LOT OWNERS FIGHT S.J.
PLAN WOULD EXTEND SUBSIDIES TO SOME  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Under the proposal, that garage and a lot at Market and San Carlos streets
will offer free parking after 6 p.m. and on weekends. Free parking would also
be available at the San Jose McEnery Convention Center after 9:30 p.m.;    A
city-subsidized validation program already available at other city-owned lots
and some private lots and garages would also be expanded, increasing the
number of subsidized parking spaces downtown to 5,240.;    Although the
McEnerys could not be reached for comment, the owners of several other lots
say they are hopping mad because the expanded freebies will lure customers
away. Attorney James Boccardo, who owns several lots, has fired off a letter
to Mayor Susan Hammer warning that "unless sober second thought" prevails, the
parking firms will sue, claiming unfair government competition with private
business.;    The private firms also claim the city has vastly underestimated
the money it will lose. Currently, the city estimates lost revenue at some
$217,000 annually. The new program would cost another $150,000 in annual lost
parking fees, according to staff estimates.;    But private-lot owners say the
real cost could be five times as high, based on the current $3-per-night
charge imposed at most downtown lots.;    A "total realistic cost" would be
closer to $2.3 million annually, concluded Albert Schlarmann, a CityPark
executive. That would include staffing garages -- like the one under the
Pavilion -- that participate in the validation program, and lost weekend
daytime revenue and other labor costs, he said.;    Joe Bass, the city's
director of streets and traffic, said he has not seen the private-lot owners'
figures, though he admitted that the costs of the program are "probably
higher" than staff estimates that were developed a few years ago.;    "I doubt
if it's in the millions," Bass said, guessing that the expansion would cost
less than $200,000.;    City politicians, who have bemoaned the downtown
parking situation for years -- and who have to listen to merchants complain
about slow business -- seem anxious to do something more to lure more people
downtown.;    "All the city facilities ought to be part of the program," said
Councilman David Pandori, who represents the downtown.;    The city council is
scheduled to consider the expansion concept next week, with a finalized plan
completed by September. Bass acknowledges that private parking firms have "a
valid point . . . this is going to affect some of them.";    "But they're
still surviving. The lots we see still seem to be functioning well."  </TEXT>
