<LEADPARA>  San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer plans to step up efforts to lure the Giants away
from San Francisco by asking for $640,000 to pay consultants to study the
design, site and financing for a proposed South Bay stadium.;   Hammer's plan
-- expected to be announced at a news conference today -- includes $200,000 to
begin designing the stadium at Highway 237 and Zanker Road before voters
approve the site or the plan.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GIANT PLANS STEP UP
HAMMER SEEKS CONSULTANT FEES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Expects majority backing; Hammer will make her request at next Tuesday's
council meeting and said she expects the majority of San Jose's council
members will back her plans.;   "If you're about to undertake the biggest
project ever in the city, it seems to me that you spend a bit of money
beforehand to make it work," the mayor said Tuesday.;   The money would be
taken from $10 million that was set aside earlier this year by the city's
redevelopment agency for economic development around the stadium site. No one
has provided estimates of how much it would cost to build the stadium.;
Action sought before vote; Hammer will ask that the $200,000 design fund be
spent before residents vote on a stadium plan next April or June. If voters
approve, spending money now will ensure that the stadium can be finished
before April 1996, according to Deputy City Manager Darrell Dearborn.;   "To
preserve the schedule we'll need to spend that money in advance," said
Dearborn. "To ensure that it is constructed in 40 months we may need to begin
architectural design before an election.";   City ordinances forbid San Jose
from building a stadium without voter approval. However, City Attorney Joan
Gallo said those ordinances don't prevent the city from doing exploratory work
on a stadium.;   In addition to the $200,000 design fund, Hammer wants to set
aside $320,000 for attorney Stan Berliner, who negotiated with the Giants
during last year's unsuccessful attempt to get county voters to pass a stadium
proposal.;   Berliner's contract would cover all negotiations with the
baseball team as well as negotiations with the state of California for 55
acres that the state owns within the 138-acre proposed stadium site. Berliner
also would research the legality of using taxes or other financing to build
the stadium.;   Berliner was paid $366,567 by the Joint Powers Authority, the
city-county agency that oversaw last year's failed Santa Clara stadium plans,
and was criticized by some associated with that deal for charging exorbitant
rates.;   In the current contract, he said he is giving San Jose a "government
rate" that cuts $40 off the usual hourly rate of Berliner partners and up to
30 percent off the rate of associates and paralegals.;   He also said that
although he has helped the San Jose Sharks hockey team negotiate a lease with
the city, he has no conflict of interest now working for the city with the
Giants.;   Gary Robinson, Hammer's chief of staff, said Berliner was chosen
because of his past experience in Giants negotiations. He also finished a
$20,000 contract with the city this summer for which he and Dearborn traveled
to Baltimore, Denver, Cleveland, Arlington, Va., and Milwaukee to study new
stadium proposals and financing plans.;   Hammer's request also includes
$25,000 for unforeseen costs and $95,000 for two financial advisers -- Tim
Mueller of Peat Marwick, who worked with the JPA during last year's stadium
negotiations, and Sam Katz of Philadelphia's Public Financing Management, who
advised the Giants. Dearborn said Katz helped pioneer the idea of financing a
stadium with the sales of luxury boxes at Miami's Joe Robbie Stadium.;
Hammer's support on the council appears solid, but some members, including
Trixie Johnson and David Pandori, questioned whether the consultants cost too
much.;   "I'm willing to go down the road for a while yet," Johnson said,
adding doubtfully, "It's an awful lot of money." Asked for her position, she
said, "It's a yes, but I haven't signed off on the dollar amount yet.";
Pandori said Berliner's contract may be too expensive, but agreed that the
city needs to spend some money to develop a ballot proposal.;   "Obviously we
can't just make one up," Pandori said.;   Meanwhile, the city of Santa Clara
is putting together a rival proposal for a stadium at the site voters
considered last year.;   The Santa Clara City Council voted Tuesday to spend
up to $37,500 to hire a congressional lobbyist to push an amendment to the
1986 federal tax law that would get the city tax-free financing for a joint
public and private stadium. The money was a loan from the general fund to the
city's Sports and Open Space Authority.;   However, congressional sources were
doubtful that the city could get such an amendment passed.  </TEXT>
