<LEADPARA>  San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer, facing a second straight year of lousy financial
news, gave her prescription Tuesday for an ailing city budget: the deepest
spending cuts of the past decade, a hiring freeze starting this week, and a
new gambling tax on card rooms.;   The city is short an estimated $20.6
million for next year's spending plan of $433 million, a bill due starting
July 1992. The city council appears ready to swallow most of the medicine, but
with little enthusiasm.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. WEIGHS NEW TAX, DEEP CUTS
MAYOR TO URGE HIRING FREEZE, GAMBLING LEVY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Chart attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "We're getting to a point now where we don't have so many choices," said
Councilman Jim Beall. "We're desperately trying to avoid laying off people.
We're into pain now, real deep pain.";   Hammer is asking City Manager Les
White to plan cuts for most city departments of 9 percent, with 2 percent for
the police and fire departments. Then the city council will choose from these
measures next spring when it approves a new annual budget.;   Such cuts
haven't been talked about since the 1982 recession and the 1978 property tax
rollbacks from Proposition 13.;   "This is by far the worst I've seen," said
Hammer, who first ran for city council in 1982. Five months ago, the mayor and
council balanced a budget gap of equal magnitude for the fiscal year that
began July 1.;   Then, the city had healthy reserves. Now, the treasury is
thin.;   Hammer's recommendations, which she will spell out at a news
conference this afternoon:;   (check) Freeze hiring across the board, except
for sworn police and firefighters. The more jobs kept open now, the mayor
reasoned, the easier it will be to shuffle employees after cuts are enacted,
avoiding layoffs. This step nets $5 million through June, from which $3
million would be applied toward the next fiscal year's deficit.;   (check)
Shift $3.8 million from a savings kitty left over from last year, and skim $1
million from a separate fund for streets and traffic improvements.;   (check)
Tax city card clubs, which now pay only token annual fees, raising nearly $2.5
million. Most council members and Hammer are high on this tax. The owners of
the Garden City card club, San Jose's largest, have reportedly agreed to it,
but they could not be reached for comment. The mayor also wants to look at
several other new fees and taxes, but the gambling tax was singled out as the
easiest first hit.;   (check) Find $10.3 million in spending cuts --
essentially half the shortfall. City Manager White said he "generally agrees"
with this strategy. "We're going to have to bite the bullet harder this time,"
he said. Police and fire will probably be insulated from most cuts, but
libraries, park maintenance and other basic services will be threatened. So
will the staffs of the mayor and council.;   The council, which plans to
debate these proposals Thursday, was moody about the news and divided on a few
points.;   "I'm not quite sure the freeze is going to work, because we froze
last year," said Councilman George Shirakawa.;   Said Councilman David
Pandori: "The hiring freeze was overdue. It should have been done four months
ago.";   The economic mess, caused in large part by slumping sales tax and
property tax revenues, could force the council to start taking a more
pro-growth, pro-business stance on development issues.;   Hammer, for example,
was talking up the building of a baseball stadium in North San Jose and
development of an industrial park planned for the city's southern fringe.;
The Coyote Valley Research Park, just north of a controversial housing
preserve, exists in name only. If businesses were to approach City Hall about
starting "Silicon Valley South," Hammer said, "Let me tell you, they'll get
the open-door, first-class treatment from every department in this city.";
The mayor also said she would take a long look at a new tax on cigarettes, if
