<LEADPARA>  EVEN police Sgt. David Wysuph says Pamela and Bill Resch have a "lovely"
home.;   On July 7, the San Jose Police vice officer attended -- undercover --
Pamela Resch's performance of music by Beethoven, Liszt, Mompou and Chopin in
her living room, for the ticket price of $25. He then had her husband Bill
arrested for conducting a business in their home without a license.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOME IS WHERE THE ART WAS
SAN JOSE POLICE RAID
CLASSICAL MUSIC CONCERT AT RESCH HOME  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story; See also related article on page 1D of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Nestled near San Jose State University, with its English garden and
stained-glass windows, the two-story house is an ideal setting for the Reschs'
19th-century-style recitals, what Pamela Resch now calls "my criminal
activities as a concert pianist.";   On that Sunday afternoon in July, concert
guests watched as uniformed police finger-printed Bill Resch -- jazz musician,
music teacher, trumpeter and orchestra coordinator for the San Jose Civic
Light Opera -- on his front lawn, in his tuxedo.;   "We couldn't believe what
we were seeing," says Cathy Yoshimoto, a Los Gatos resident who attended with
family and friends. "(The police) could have been more discreet. It was
obviously not a rock concert or a brothel. Why would they make such a scene?";
  It is a scene that has brought to a halt the Reschs' 7-year-long series of
classical music concerts -- even though the charges have been dropped. It is
also a scene that has aroused the support of friends, guests, neighbors, city
councilman David Pandori, Supervisor Zoe Lofgren -- and even conservative
pundit William F. Buckley Jr.;   Support pours in; Supporters have inundated
the mayor's office with letters protesting the arrest and pleading for the
concerts to continue. Buckley, who hosted a concert by Pamela Resch in his New
York home, wrote in an Aug. 19 letter to Mayor Susan Hammer:;   "I do hope you
will intervene in the matter and uphold the singular reputation San Jose
enjoys as a town hospitable to fine artistic events." Both Hammer and Buckley
were unavailable for comment.;   The issue will be heard by the city council
Nov. 19, when Pandori, representing the downtown area, will introduce a
proposal allowing the concerts to continue.;   "Good music isn't limited to
big concert halls," Pandori says. "We should bring the local zoning code up to
date to allow this activity in someone's home, with appropriate controls to
make sure it doesn't impact on adjacent areas.";   "I don't have to think
twice about supporting Pamela," says Yoshimoto, who plans to attend the
meeting. "We have to save her gift to the community. She's one of San Jose's
treasures.";   "I never knew a community could be so supportive -- once you
feel that strength behind you, you don't feel afraid anymore," says Pamela
Resch, a San Jose native who has performed world-wide.;   "I'm hopeful the
issue will be resolved," says Supervisor Lofgren. Of the police investigation,
she adds, "To put that kind of effort into something that isn't bothering
anyone -- when you've got drive-by shootings -- is bizarre.";   Upholding the
law; Wysuph says "this is not the crime of the century," but adds it was
"simply a case we followed up on. (The Reschs) were running a commercial
enterprise in violation of the law.";   "I'm not into people violating rules,"
Lofgren says, "but part of having a great city is allowing events like this to
flourish.";   Wysuph himself says of the event: "It was a wonderful afternoon.
(Pamela Resch) is an accomplished pianist. And if she were performing legally,
I would not hesitate to attend one of her concerts on my own time.";   But the
police sergeant may not get that chance, unless the city finds a way to
resolve the issue.;   The problem, Bill Resch says, is a "Kafka-esque
nightmare. The city says 'get a business license,' then it says we can't get
one. One hand says we can keep the concerts if we pay back-taxes; another hand
says pay the back-taxes but discontinue the concerts; a third hand says don't
pay anything and we'll try to find a way to keep the concerts. It's nuts down
there; no one seems to know what's going on.";   Meanwhile, the Reschs are
pinning their hopes on the upcoming city council meeting and on Hammer, who
wrote in a July 29 letter to Lofgren: "I am working . . . to find a way to
allow the recitals to continue.";   The city has never received complaints
about the concerts. It was a newspaper ad placed by the Reschs in the Metro
weekly for their June concerts that attracted the vice squad's attention. The
squad often scans ads for leads on illegal activities, Wysuph says.;   "We
thought perhaps there was a violation in the dispensation of alcohol without a
license," he says. The ad describes concert refreshments as: "complimentary
drinks, killer brownies, cheese puffs.";   The issue, says Chris O'Hanlan of
San Jose's Alcohol Beverage Control, "was brought to my attention by the San
Jose Vice Unit. I gave Mr. Resch a call (on June 21) and let him know in a
low-key style that if he offers alcoholic beverages and takes money for
tickets, that constitutes a sale. He didn't realize he was breaking the law.";
  Bill Resch says he told O'Hanlan: " 'Then we'll stop doing it."' Mr.
O'Hanlan said he'd call the vice squad and let them know. I thought that was
the end of it.";   But it wasn't the end of it. For one thing, O'Hanlan and
Wysuph disagree on whether paying guests can bring their own alcohol to the
recitals.;   O'Hanlan says, "Mr. Resch asked if it was all right if people
brought their own (alcohol). I didn't see a problem with it.";   Wysuph does.
"Charging admission to the recitals and allowing guests to bring their own
alcohol (is) still on the dark side of the law." In any case, Wysuph says,
"The alcohol was not cited for.";   "The next thing I knew," O'Hanlan says,
"there was a question if (the Reschs) were operating without a business
license. That's out of our jurisdiction.";   "We attended the concert," Wysuph
says. "She (Pamela Resch) was running a business from her residence, and she
was operating a commercial enterprise inside a residential zone. That's what
she was issued a citation for.";   Husband takes the rap; But it was Bill
Resch, not Pamela, who was cited.;   "That's another strange little twist,"
says Pamela Resch. "It's the Pamela Resch salon concerts. But the police
arrested Billy. Don't you think it was sexist of them to arrest Billy --
instead of me?;   "I'm not anxious to be arrested, but what happened to Billy
is obscene. I hope nothing like this happens to another artist ever again."  </TEXT>
