<DESCRIPT>  POLITICS; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  You may have followed the stories recently about KQED-TV's lawsuit to make the
death penalty safe for home viewing. Technically, that case is still hanging
fire -- although it looks as though the warden of San Quentin will prevail in
his efforts to close the execution to all the media. One intriguing sidelight
dealt with just who the Deukmejian administration initially selected as press
witnesses. Before the KQED suit, the San Quentin administration picked 14
reporters by name, including the now-retired Jack Schriebman of the Associated
Press; Anne Krueger of the San Diego Tribune; Dan Morain of the Los Angeles
Times, Larry Hatfield of the San Francisco Examiner; Barbara Simpson, then of
KCBS radio; and Rebecca LaVally, of Gannett News Service.; When it looked like
execution for Robert Alton Harris -- the famous Cheeseburger Killer -- the
list was then passed on to Deukmejian's press secretary, Bob Gore. Gore
specified only news organizations, not reporters. His reasoning was that the
state shouldn't make assignments. But there was at least one noticeable
oddity. For Sacramento, Gore picked the NBC television affiliate and the
Sacramento Union, not its far larger competitor, the Sacramento Bee. KQED's
attorneys seized on this as evidence of favoritism, asking Gore whether this
was because of unfavorable columns by the Bee's Dan Walters. Our television
writer David Rosenthal, who covered the trial, says that Gore denied the
charge. Gore said Walters' work had no impact on selection. But the press
secretary wasn't able to remember why he chose the right-wing Union over the
liberal Bee. FYI: The Mercury News was omitted from Gore's list. Not so the
San Francisco Chronicle and the Examiner.  </LEADPARA>
