<TEXT>  INVOKING GHOSTS; Ex-San Jose Council Member Lu Ryden may be gone from public
office. Her spirit, however, lives on. Last week, the council invited her back
to give the invocation. And naturally, it was proceeded by a little banter.
When Mayor Susan Hammer asked Ryden how she was enjoying her retirement, she
replied, "Tremendously. I've been reading the paper every day and enjoying it
even more," an obvious reference to the city's financial woes. Echoing Abe
Lincoln, Ryden then reminded the council that "God put you here to rule over
people . . . for the benefit of the people." She asked God's blessing on the
11 council members, saying, "They need your guidance (because they face) many
temptations . . . keep them from the temptation of putting their own needs
first. . . . Help them also to realize that even though they're here for a
short time, their decisions can be felt for a lifetime."; A PARTISAN PAEAN;
The good thing about blue-ribbon panels is that there are no strings attached.
Well, hardly any strings. Take the list of folks who have been appointed by
the city council to draw new districts for city elections. The chairman,
Richard Garcia, is a former member of the San Jose Unified School Board. Steve
Schell is a spokesman for Hewlett-Packard. Sherri Sager is an aide to
Supervisor Mike Honda. Brian Grayson is an aide to Norm Mineta. Professor H.
Brett Melendy is married to Marion Melendy, an aide to Nancy Ianni. And the
august John Marshall Collins, appointed by Councilman David Pandori, is the
husband of Supervisor Zoe Lofgren. Lofgren, you may remember, endorsed Pandori
in the last election. All told, a savvy group. Rest assured that someone's
interest will be protected.; TO THE HUSTINGS;    A few bits and pieces: Bob
Livengood, the director of the Building Industry Association, is stepping down
as of May 3 to go back to managing his three 7-11 stores. Livengood has not
ruled out another try for public office, possibly for Dom Cortese's Assembly
seat. Insiders at City Hall speculate that his departure may give the BIA a
reason to ask for delay in various fee increases planned by the council.
That's what happened two years ago when Livengood took over.  . . Political
consultants Roger Lee and Carol Beddo have signed on attorney and developer
Phil DiNapoli as a client. In fact, we're told they plan to move into
DiNapoli's building in Park Center Plaza. . . . Finally, the Oakland City
Council's rules committee has bestowed two seats in the city's skybox at A's
games to former Mayor Lionel Wilson. "It's a nice gesture," said current Mayor
Elihu Harris. (box)  </TEXT>
