<LEADPARA>  For years, even as San Jose police were desperately trying to shut it down,
city officials were able to count on their friends at the local poker parlor
for big campaign bucks.;   Now, struggling with a second consecutive $20
million-plus budget deficit, council members hope the biggest card room in
Northern California will help bail them out to the tune of at least $2 million
a year.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. GAMBLES ON CARD CLUB TAX
CITY FORESEES GARDEN OF CASH  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     And some police and other law enforcement officials wonder whether the
city's new reliance on the club as a cash cow might not mean carte blanche for
Garden City should it want to expand, increase the current $200 betting limit
or add games.;   San Jose actually has three card clubs, but it is the
40-table Garden City that will bear the brunt of a proposed new tax that would
siphon up to 11.5 percent of the club's gross receipts into the city's general
fund.;   In a climate under which most businesses would balk at new taxes,
Garden City is unique. Club executives actually suggested a new tax earlier
this year.;   The club's business has been booming since it introduced "Asian
games" earlier this year. More than 100 new employees have been registered
with the police department, and the parking lot at Stevens Creek Boulevard and
Saratoga Avenue is overflowing -- so full that the club now leases space down
the block for employee parking and runs a shuttle bus to the club.;   That
apparent prosperity is the direct result of city council approval of ordinance
changes that allowed the new games.;   Though club officials suggested the new
tax some time before part-owner Nicholas J. Dalis approached the council about
the new high-stakes games, Mayor Susan Hammer said at the time that the two
issues were not related.;   Hammer announced her plans to study a gross
receipts tax on March 20, the day after the council approved the lucrative new
games.;   Dalis and other Garden City executives did not return telephone
calls, but they have not publicly complained about the proposal, which would
boost their annual fees and taxes from about $250,000 to almost 10 times
that.;   Hammer, who prefers to think of the card room tax as "a fantastic
source of revenue for the city," has also considered such taxes to help pay
for a new baseball stadium. She dismissed questions about whether she now
would feel pressured to help the club expand, and bolster city coffers even
more.;   "I don't know," she said. "I haven't really thought about that.";
Pandori against expansion;   David Pandori, one of three council members who
voted against the new games, said it makes sense to tax the club as long as
it's there, but that he will not vote for any expansion or new games.;
Deputy City Manager Darrell Dearborn, who oversees the city budget, said the
council "just needs to be aware" of the situation when it considers other
rules for the club.;   Dearborn is more concerned about another possibility.
He fears that the city will become dependent on income that could evaporate if
Garden City loses its license, a threat that has been hanging over the club
and 11 officers and employees since they were indicted in 1987.;   "It's a
source of revenue that may not be dependable," Dearborn said of the proposed
new tax. "As they go, so goes the revenue source.";   Skimming indictments;
The Garden City principals face conspiracy and tax charges stemming from an
alleged multimillion-dollar skimming operation, and 10 of the 11 are charged
with violating state campaign contribution laws. Investigators believe they
tried to expand their political pull by arranging for dozens of club employees
to make campaign contributions that the club later reimbursed. A trial date is
scheduled to be set Dec. 17.;   Since the indictment, most of the employee
contributions have stopped, but Garden City officials continue to be generous.
For example, Dalis and club associates contributed more than $6,000 to Hammer
last year. Councilwoman Blanca Alvarado got at least $3,250, and most other
council members also pulled in hefty contributions.;   Former Police Chief
Joseph McNamara, who said he would yank the club's license if Dalis and the
others were convicted, called the new tax "cynical.";   'Cynical way' to raise
money;   "I think it would be questionable for the council to rely on a source
of income from a business that has been accused of ill behavior a number of
times, with an indictment and criminal case pending. That's a pretty cynical
way for government to raise funds . . . by raising fees of someone accused of
breaking those laws the council has passed -- and state law.";   McNamara's
successor, Lou Cobarruviaz, said he, too, would rescind Garden City's license
if convictions result.;   But meanwhile, he does not oppose the tax.;   "I
realize the city is in a critical situation. . . . We have to be practical,"
Cobarruviaz said.;   Even if Dalis or any of the others is convicted, and the
license is revoked, there is still a chance that others could buy out the
shareholders and hold on to the license by "cleaning house.";   The city's
card room ordinance gives the police chief authority over license transfers,
but Cobarruviaz said he believes that Hammer and the council should decide
that policy issue.  </TEXT>
