<LEADPARA>  Cajoled by Mayor Susan Hammer and a stream of developers, labor leaders and
civic bigwigs, the San Jose City Council voted Tuesday to put $640,000 toward
a ballot date next spring with the San Francisco Giants.;   Zeroing in on a
site near Highway 237 and Zanker Road, the council agreed to begin various
stadium studies and sign a contract with attorney Stan Berliner to negotiate
land deals and ballpark financing with the baseball club.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. OKS $640,000 FOR BALLPARK CAMPAIGN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The vote on half of the funding was a unanimous 11-0. But Councilman David
Pandori voted against the $320,000 pact with Berliner, saying it was too
expensive.;   Because the $640,000 was taken from the Redevelopment Agency's
long-range budget, agency officials calculated that the financial impact four
years down the road actually would be $860,000. This would account for
interest lost by spending the money earlier than planned. But Hammer said the
higher figure was "totally misleading.";   The council rhetoric was
predictable. Most argued, as Hammer did last week, that money needs to be
spent before the city can reliably estimate the ballpark's cost, which so far
is a huge unknown. Sample: "This is a basic plan to get some facts before the
voters," said Councilman Jim Beall.;   But what the public said was more
lively. Some words were heated, some highfalutin, and some just plain hot
air.;   Paul Freiman, chairman of Syntex Corp., said San Jose would evoke the
glories of Socratic Athens in ancient Greece. "San Jose is rapidly approaching
a new height as a city," Freiman said.;   Testimonials piled on from
organizations such as the Associated General Contractors of Santa Clara
Valley, the San Jose Police Officers' Association, the Building Industry
Association and the Central Labor Council of Santa Clara and San Benito
counties.;   Marian Holt, president of the San Jose Convention &amp; Visitors
Bureau, had the best hyperbole of the day. "We might even think about renaming
our bay, to San Jose Bay," she said.;   Grumpy taxpayers, too, had their say.
"I object to organizations such as the Giants who expect public money to pay
for million-dollar baseball players," said Virgil McVicker.;   Said the
like-minded Ross Signorino, "Mr. Lurie and the Giants will be making millions
at the poor people's expense.";   Perhaps the most understated commentary was
offered by Jordan Spaulding, who lives in Mobilepark West, on Nicholson Lane
near the stadium site. "Why was the Zanker Road site preferred over others?"
he asked. "What kind of information will we have regarding noise, and stadium
lights, and traffic?";   Hammer replied that Spaulding and other critics would
get a full airing of their concerns about the stadium's site and cost when the
council next takes up the issue, in December or January. Until then, the
ballpark drive is back in the hands of consultants and a small army of mostly
anonymous city officials.  </TEXT>
