<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; MAYOR; DEVELOPMENT; POLICY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  UST before squeaking by Frank Fiscalini to become mayor of San Jose last year,
Susan Hammer sounded as if she would personify the unbroken chain of rational
urban planning that stretched from Norm Mineta to Janet Gray Hayes to Tom
McEnery.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Perspective  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HAMMER POUNDING ON DOOR OF GROWTH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Philip J. Trounstine, the Mercury News political editor, writes on local,
state and national politics.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "You can't be talking about neighborhood services on the one hand and
expanding the urban service area on the other," she said in an interview at
the Mercury News. "It doesn't work. It dilutes from those services.";
Defending her role in the November 1988 6-5 vote to convert 54 acres of prime
industrial land to build housing, Hammer said:;   "That was a unique piece of
property. That was included in the Edenvale industrial reserve by a council
that I wasn't a part of. It's not contiguous to any of the other industrial
reserve. It's surrounded on a couple of sides by housing.";   Although she had
in fact been a member of the council that brought the land into the city
limits in May 1983 specifically for industry, Hammer's statement -- and her
defense of Coyote Valley this summer -- seemed to suggest that the decision to
convert Edenvale land for homes was "a one-instance thing.";   Now we know it
wasn't.;   Hammer's slow-growth rhetoric, with which she tagged Fiscalini and
Councilwoman Shirley Lewis as more pro-growth than she, looks now less
indicative of her true outlook than her earlier "housing, housing, housing"
mantra.;   Despite her contention that it is being "blown out of proportion,"
the recent 8-3 vote converting an additional 92 acres of Edenvale industrial
land for up to 990 homes represents the most significant breach of planning
philosophy and practice in San Jose in the past 20 years.;   Not since the
first urban development policy was adopted by San Jose in 1970 has any mayor
presided over a land-use change that was so thoroughly opposed by planners,
economic development officials and redevelopment experts -- not to mention
environmentalists, school districts and controlled-growth advocates.;   San
Jose, with its continuing shortage of jobs compared to housing, remains a
bedroom for job-rich cities like Palo Alto, Sunnyvale and Santa Clara.
Building new homes -- which cannot pay for the police, fire, library,
recreation and other services they demand -- is an inexorable drain on
existing residential neighborhoods.;   "The conversion of 100 acres of land
from industrial to residential land uses would have profound implications for
the future viability of the city's economic development strategy," the
planners warned.;   "The proposed amendment threatens the equilibrium that San
Jose has attempted to achieve by balancing demands associated with economic
development, housing and transportation.";   Against this line of reasoning,
developers Drew Gibson and Steve Speno (Gibson Speno), Reid Gustafson (Shea
Homes) and Roger Menard (Kaufman &amp; Broad) pointed to the regional lack of
housing as compared to jobs.;   Moreover, they argued new industry won't
locate in San Jose's Edenvale industrial area unless much more housing is
built nearby.;   Finally, they held, the Edenvale land isn't all that great
for industry anyway.;   Hammer, who let soon-to-retire Councilwoman Pat
Sausedo front for the project, was terse.;   "This community needs to do
something to give our economy a kick in the rear, if you will," she said. "I
believe it will make a very, very ideal housing site.";   Hammer's aide Margie
Fernandes expanded on the issue last week for her boss, who was out of town.;
 "She'd like to see some economic development activity -- be it in the
construction trades -- and she believes that the housing will attract
industry," Fernandes said.;   "Susan's an action-oriented mayor. A lot of us
can be planners. But she is the mayor and she is not afraid to make tough
political decisions based on reality, not on a plan that was made 10 years
ago.;   "History is fine," Fernandes said. "But we can't all get hung up on
symbols here. Susan is a real mayor of a real city.";   She is not, however,
the first "real mayor of a real city.";   Norm Mineta was the first mayor to
challenge the developers. In 1972 he forced out the late pro-growth City
Manager A.P. "Dutch" Hamann and hired controlled-growth manager Ted Tedesco.;
 In 1974, Janet Gray Hayes fought against the old guard developers and the
Mercury News to become mayor. Her slogan: "Let's make San Jose better before
we make it bigger.";   Throughout her tenure, Hayes held off attempts to crack
open Coyote Valley and -- with only a few exceptions -- to expand the city
limits.;   McEnery won the mayor's race against Councilman Claude Fletcher in
1982. His winning slogan: "It's time for San Jose to stop growing out and
start growing up." And that's what the city did during his tenure -- building
up its downtown while holding at the fringe.;   Now comes Hammer.;   In June
1989 she was already arguing that "if you don't link the housing and the
transportation with the jobs, your transportation capacity and housing are
gone before you ever get the jobs.";   "Are you talking about converting
industrial land to housing?" I asked her then.;   "No," she said. "Some of
that may have to be done. I don't know. What I want to happen is a situation
where the city is in control of this. I don't want to see a situation like
what happened last general plan (November 1988) where we began to piecemeal
these decisions and the council doesn't have any control over it.";   Although
Councilman David Pandori -- and possibly others -- are having second thoughts
about their historic piecemeal decision in Edenvale, Fernandes said the mayor
is unwavering.;   "It was the right decision," Fernandes said last week. Well
then, would Fernandes, who plans to run for city council in Berryessa, have
voted the same way?;   "I don't know," she said. "I think it's an unfair
question. . . . It was a political decision made by a political
office-holder.";   Indeed. (box)  </TEXT>
