<LEADPARA>  THE Oak Grove School District learned the hard way that you can't count on San
Jose for good city planning when powerful developers take their case to the
city council.;   Not any more.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOUSING IN NOWHERE
SAN JOSE DEVELOPMENT WOULD OVERWHELM A STRUGGLING
SCHOOL DISTRICT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The district had filed written objections to a Gibson Speno/Shea Homes
housing plan for Edenvale's industrial area. But Superintendent Anthony Russo
says he didn't show up at last week's council meeting because it never
occurred to him that the council might approve the plan -- a pocket of housing
in the middle of nowhere, pure sprawl, which goes against everything the
city's general plan has stood for.;   But Russo was in a time warp. Under
former mayor Tom McEnery, the plan would have been laughed out of City Hall.
Under Mayor Susan Hammer, developers now know that if they come up with
excuses to put housing anywhere it suits their needs, the council is ready to
listen. This plan sailed through on an 8-3 vote.;   Fortunately, some council
members are willing to listen to Russo as well. The hearing on the proposal
will be reopened Dec. 10, and the council has one last chance to stop this bad
development.;   The mayor wasn't one of those willing to listen, however.
Hammer -- who normally prides herself on bending rules for a good cause --
grasped a technicality and tried to keep Oak Grove from making its appeal. It
was Councilman David Pandori who opened the door for the district, joined by
by Joe Head and Nancy Ianni, as well as the three council members who
originally opposed the housing plan: Judy Stabile, Trixie Johnson and Shirley
Lewis.;   When Hammer was running for mayor, she published an unfair campaign
pamphlet that claimed Shirley Lewis was more pro-growth than she was. The hit
piece was based on Lewis' approval of some large developments, but this
Edenvale plan points up the real difference between Lewis and Hammer. Lewis
supports thoughtful growth based on solid planning principles. Hammer's
principles turned to putty this fall when developers came calling.;   Oak
Grove sees the problem with this housing plan that Hammer misses. It's the
isolation of the neighborhood, cut off by the freeway, which makes it
impossible to absorb the kids in existing schools and will force Oak Grove to
build a new one, at a cost of $10 million. That isolation also will make the
neighborhood difficult and expensive to provide with city services, such as
police and fire protection. It will be a drain on existing neighborhoods.;
But it will be more profitable for developers than leaving the land for
industry.;   Judy Stabile has a good suggestion. She says this tract should be
re-evaluated as part of the city-wide general plan review. Before the city
considers changing it from industrial land to housing, a task force should
examine the impacts on the schools and on city services.;   That's a sensible
approach to this proposal. That's what the council should vote for on Dec. 10.  </TEXT>
