<LEADPARA>  In the hubbub of Christmas, you may have missed the strange but intriguing
case of the electoral mother-in-law. Since it's coming to court Tuesday, we'll
replay it: Byron Pipkin and Greg Yoder, two candidates who finished out of the
running for the two four-year seats on the San Jose Unified School District
board, have brought the suit. They're alleging that one of the winners, Louis
K. "Bud" Towner, should be disqualified. Their reason? They say Towner did not
live in the district -- and that his real home was at 1054 Mitchell Court in
Campbell.;    Towner disputes this charge, calling it "sour grapes." He told
our reporter Bill Romano that he moved to his mother-in-law's home at 1070
Glenbrook Avenue in Willow Glen last August. While he acknowledges owning the
Mitchell Court property, he says his residence is in San Jose. And he has
changed his voter registration to reflect that. But not every authority got
the message. The DMV still lists Towner on Mitchell Court. County records show
he still enjoys a homeowner's exemption there. The San Jose post office, which
delivers to Mitchell Court, shows no change of address for Towner. And Pipkin
and Yoder say that neighbors have told them that Towner continues to live on
Mitchell.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Perspective  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  I AIN'T NO WANDERIN' MAN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Insider  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Whether this is enough to invalidate Towner's election will depend on the
legal interpretation of residency. But Pipkin, a Sunnyvale public safety
lieutenant who finished third after Towner and Rich Couser, says the principle
is particularly important with the onset of district elections. "If we can't
keep out someone who's not even in the district, how are they going to keep
five people in their proper districts?" he asked.; TOLD BRIEFLY;    A few bits
and pieces: Deborah Larson, the City of San Jose's finance director, quit last
week, saying she had accomplished what she intended and needed time to write
and paint. You may remember that her wedding to chief budget analyst Greg
Larson was one of City Hall's major social events last year . . . Catherine
Pandori, the wife of new council member David Pandori, showed up at the year's
first council meeting last Tuesday with the couple's 11-day-old son . . .
Expect to see a major zoo outside the new Hall of Justice on Hedding Street
when it opens tomorrow. The powers-that-be have built the courthouse before
finishing the parking garage across the street. . . . You may wonder why the
Susan Hammer inauguration went off so smoothly last Monday. It's because the
ceremony was rehearsed word for word. Little circles were even drawn for the
participants to stand in. A production of Roger Lee and Carol Beddo, who were
everywhere with their walkie-talkies  . . Wittingly or unwittingly, the new
mayor snubbed her predecessor, Tom McEnery. Hammer introduced a host of
elected officials, including San Francisco Art Agnos. She neglected to mention
McEnery. It couldn't have been a payback for his lack of endorsement. Could
it?; BREACH OF ETIQUETTE;    Has the move for term limits reached a bit of a
barrier? After San Jose and the state of California imposed term limits last
November, Councilman Norm Shaskey of Mountain View, a self-styled populist,
figured he could start a movement to do the same for the Board of Supervisors.
He figured wrong. At a council meeting Tuesday, Shaskey put forward a
resolution asking the supes to put a two-consecutive-term-limit measure before
voters. It is an idea that may not sit well with, say, Supervisor Rod Diridon,
the senior member of the board, in his fifth term. Shaskey also wanted to ask
other cities to sign up. But the motion died for lack of a second. Said
Mountain View Councilwoman Pat Figueroa: "There was no interest in it. I have
no idea why he chose to put it on. It hit us as a great big surprise."; BUY AT
THE RACK;    If you've been following the recent musical chairs game with the
valley's bureaucrats, you could make a persuasive case that the move of city
manager Thomas Frutchey from Los Altos Hills to Campbell was simply a career
step upward. When he took the $90,000 job early this month, Frutchey, 41,
praised Campbell as a place that has "has real community feeling and spirit,
based on traditional values." It's no secret in Los Altos Hills, however, that
Frutchey regularly clashed with the Mizz Nordstrom of the town council, Toni
Casey. You may remember her as the one who suggested a while back that the
town government should emulate Nordstrom's standard of service. "There's been
a feeling that Tom can't get anything done," said one of our sources. "He's
frustrated personally." Frutchey, incidentally, is the second high-ranking
town official to depart recently: City Planner Ann Jamison is also gone.  </TEXT>
