<LEADPARA>  The San Jose City Council's vote in Wednesday's early hours for new housing in
Edenvale marked a watershed for the city's growth policy, with portents for
developers, would-be politicians, the San Jose economy, underfunded schools
and Silicon Valley home buyers.;   The five hours of debate leading up to the
council's 7-4 vote for hundreds of new homes in Edenvale showed that changing
92 acres from industry to housing use was more than a simple matter of
recoloring San Jose's planning maps, despite Mayor Susan Hammer's initial
gambit to downplay the issue.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EDENVALE VOTE REFLECTS EASIER GROWTH POLICY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Analysis  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     For Hammer, who conceded that the hearing had raised her consciousness
about the straits of schools, the vote was above all a worthwhile gamble to
catalyze San Jose's economy.;   She knew the housing would burden the Oak
Grove School District and East Side Union High School District. She knew that
beat cops and fire trucks and parks crews would be challenged to cover new
ground in the city's southeast corner. But she couldn't pass up a chance to
make San Jose more marketable.;   "It is better to face the problems of
economic growth rather than economic stagnation," the mayor told perhaps 200
people, from an original crowd of nearly 700, who stayed after midnight to
witness the red and green flashes on the vote board. "That is the very, very
heart of the reason I supported this general plan amendment.";   For
developers, who struggled with then-Mayor Tom McEnery through most of the
1980s, the vote signaled that the council is ready to make a deal even if the
city's professional staff is unanimously opposed.;   The Gibson Speno Co. and
Shea Homes can now cash in an option secured during the height of the McEnery
era from landowners headed by businessman Richard Levin. Though the general
plan allows up to 990 homes on the property, east of Highway 101 and Coyote
Creek, the developers, allied with Kaufman &amp; Broad South Bay Inc., plan to
build 600.;   With prices from $150,000 (for attached townhomes and condos) to
about $300,000 (for detached homes), the developers will make plenty of money
even if fees and assessments are heavier than usual.;   For home buyers, the
vote showed a council anxious to build new homes in new neighborhoods, at
prices aimed toward Silicon Valley professionals. Council members Joe Head,
Pat Sausedo and George Shirakawa drilled this point over and over, but the
affordability of the homes for first-time buyers remains debatable.;   "I'm
unwilling to believe that the fiscal situation in the (school) district and
the city is such that our only reasonable choice is to do nothing and give
up," said Head, who is up for re-election next spring. "This is a good plan
for housing, for families, on the most affordable scale that private industry
can provide.";   For declared and potential council candidates, the vote meant
a new political issue for 1992, when five seats are at stake. Judi Brauns and
Robert Perro, of the southern District 2, and J. Manuel Herrera, of Berryessa
District 4, spoke against the project. Terry Hayden, in Evergreen District 8,
spoke for it.;   "People who live there are opposed to it, so my position is
no," said Perro.;   For the schools -- backed by council members Judy Stabile,
David Pandori, Shirley Lewis and Trixie Johnson -- the vote meant more budgets
written with cuts and prayers. Officials from the Oak Grove elementary and
East Side high school districts pleaded for a no vote or guarantees that the
new neighborhood's impacts would be wiped clean by developers.;   Oak Grove
and Shea Homes were making progress in talks before the vote, but not enough
to change the district's stance. Shea put forward a package said by a
developer and a Hammer aide to be worth $4 million, aiming for but not
guaranteeing a new elementary school east of the freeway. District officials
valued the package somewhat lower, and kept their bargaining line of $10
million for a new school.;   Superintendent Anthony Russo put the dilemma in
words the council could understand: "It would be analogous to the city taking
its operating dollars for parks, and buying another park, and then trying to
maintain them all. They would all deteriorate.";   Hammer's response was warm
words ("We all, we all, share that concern") and a proposed new task force to
study school fees early next year. But to Oak Grove parents, the mayor's
sympathy seemed insincere.;   Said Debbie Peevyhouse: "I don't know what her
motivation was, but it wasn't for the people. That wasn't in her heart."  </TEXT>
