<LEADPARA>  Faced with a 45 percent cut in its water use, the city of San Jose has taken a
water-conservation step that will not save any water. But it might help the
city's image.;    All city-owned fountains will be turned off.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  S.J. CUTS FOUNTAIN FLOWS
WATER SAVINGS SEEN AS SYMBOLIC  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Cathie Calvert contributed to this report.
Drought Year 5  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The city council voted to turn off the fountains -- even though they use
reclaimed water -- because they give the "perception" of wasting water.;    "I
can appreciate that argument, but the reason I voted against it is that we're
feeding the misconception" that the city has been wasting water in the
fountains, said Councilman David Pandori.;    "That's what is ironic. We're
going to shut off the fountains, and we're going to have to use the same
amount of water to shut them off.";    Even though the fountains won't be
working, they will remain full of water, because if the fountains are left
dry, the plaster in them deteriorates. Among the fountains to be shut off are
the ones at the Center for Performing Arts, Plaza Park, the old convention
center, the new convention center, the Children's Discovery Museum and St.
James Park. The fountains along the transit mall will also stop spouting.;
"The difficulty we face is that if the fountains are on, people get the
impression that we're not serious about saving water," said Councilman Joe
Head, who, along with Pandori and Councilwoman Shirley Lewis, voted against
turning them off.;    "The symbology says we're serious, even though the
actual turning off of the fountains doesn't save anything.";    Head said
water used in the fountains is all reclaimed water that gets dumped into the
bay if it is not used. The reclaimed water is not suitable for drinking, but
is perfectly suited for watering trees or operating fountains.;    The
reclaimed water comes from two places -- the city's sewage treatment plant and
an underground spring on the San Jose International Airport property.;
According to Michelle Yesney, director of the Office of Environmental
Management, the city has been using reclaimed water from the "dewatering
operation" at the airport to fill the downtown fountains for the past two
years.;    The new parking garage and baggage terminal are on top of the
underground spring, and the city has to pump about 100,000 gallons each day
into a pond so the buildings won't flood. Head said that at some point, the
city will use that water to nourish the airport landscaping.;    Councilwoman
Judy Stabile voted for turning off the fountains because, she said, allowing
the fountains to run sends the wrong message to San Jose residents.;    "It's
an irritant to people to see the fountains running in the middle of a
drought," Stabile said. "We know it's reclaimed water, but the general public
doesn't know that. The message should be that we're all in this together and
that saving water, even if it's in small amounts, is important.";    Council
members say the fountain shutoff is the first step in a series of water
cutbacks they will have to make to meet the impending Santa Clara Valley Water
District rationing levels. In addition to shutting down the fountains, the
council also decided in a separate vote to ban plantings on public lands,
including parks, until 1992 and to suspend the surface watering of mature
trees.;    Also under consideration are a variety of measures from postponing
new parks to forbidding developers from landscaping planned housing tracts.  </TEXT>
