<LEADPARA>  From the steely glass edifices of downtown, to the leafy streets of Willow
Glen, to the raw new tracts of Evergreen and Berryessa, city council politics
is crackling through San Jose with more electricity than at anytime in the
past decade.;   A new two-term limit will bump four councilwomen from the
10-member council after 1992, meaning that local politics could be just as
lively next year as, say, the twin U.S. Senate races crisscrossing California.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COUNCIL POLITICS PULSING IN S.J.
HOT RACES SEEN FOR 4 OPENINGS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "It's a free-for-all. It's crazy," said Carl Lindstrom, one of as many as
half a dozen candidates eyeing the North San Jose seat Shirley Lewis won in
1980.;   The same could be said of Judy Stabile's South San Jose district,
Nancy Ianni's Willow Glen district, and Pat Sausedo's sprawling southeast
district. These Democrats have formed the core of a liberal, environmentalist
council for most of the 1980s. The term limit passed last year knocked the
struts from under that core.;   Republicans could capitalize on the openings.
The GOP now has no voice on the ostensibly non-partisan council -- a total
shutout. Dan Minutillo, a former mayoral and council candidate, hopes to
change that.;   "We will have Republicans in every single council race," said
Minutillo, who heads a group that calls itself the "Republican Candidate
Development Committee." "It's a great opportunity. We can't go much lower than
we actually are.";   Traditionally, parks, crime and traffic are the meat and
potatoes of council elections. But citywide issues could supplant parochial
concerns next year, especially if a baseball stadium measure is on the spring
ballot.;   Lewis' District 4 -- encompassing Berryessa and, for now, Alviso --
illustrates forces pulsing throughout the city: mayoral influence, council
heir-making, redistricting wrangling and emerging ethnic power.;   The
District 4 race will test Mayor Susan Hammer's strength after her first year
in office. Hammer's longtime aide, Margie Fernandes, now the mayor's land-use
policy director, has all but declared her candidacy. Fernandes is now making
the back-room rounds for endorsements. She plans to leave her city job Jan. 1
to run full time.;   '1,000 percent' backing; Hammer has said Fernandes will
have her support "1,000 percent," meaning that the 45-year-old aide should
have plenty of money.;   Lewis is expected to back Chuck Reed, 43, the
attorney who directed her failed 1990 mayoral campaign-- if he decides to run.
Reed admits he is still iffy, but Lewis would make a potent patron.;   Carm
Grande, 55, the fireplug former leader of the San Jose Police Officers'
Association, said he's running. Grande, a former Republican who just switched
his registration to "decline to state," will probably get lots of ink simply
for his populist quotability.;   He's already ripping Hammer and Fernandes,
painting them as insiders, out of touch with "average folks" like him. "Is
Margie Fernandes going to come out and criticize redevelopment?" Grande asked,
tauntingly. "She can't. She's part of it. Margie Fernandes is not going to
shoot her benefactor in the foot.";   'Berryessa insider'; Fernandes wouldn't
take the bait. Her reply: "I'm a Berryessa insider. I've been volunteering in
Berryessa much longer than I've been working for the city of San Jose.";   Ben
Menor, 41, a former aide to Supervisor Ron Gonzales and a Philippines native,
is running from another platform altogether: Berryessa's growing Asian
population. During the 1980s, the district's Asian population rose by 20,300,
an increase of more than 200 percent. Menor moved into Berryessa a year ago,
but he said he has been planning to run for the past 20 years and lists a
string of grass-roots Filipino activities to back it up.;   Menor may have to
fight Lindstrom for that base. Lindstrom, 37, is also Filipino. A Democratic
Party activist, Lindstrom acknowledges that he needs solid Asian support. But
in the next breath, he says: "I'm not running as a 'minority candidate.' The
challenge of an ethnic candidate is to transcend his community and run in the
mainstream.";   J. Manuel Herrera, elected last year to the board of the East
Side Union High School District, is also thinking about running.;   Awaiting
remapping; Like candidates elsewhere, the District 4 bunch is waiting to see
what happens this fall with the city's political maps. It's hard to start a
candidacy when you don't know who your voters will be.;   The once-a-decade
