<LEADPARA>  IT'S NOT that certain San Jose cops have any distaste for classical music or
consider Beethoven, Chopin and Liszt any threat to the community.;    In fact,
vice squad Sgt. David Wysuph and Officer Jim Roach said they enjoyed the piano
recital they attended undercover a couple of Sundays ago at the home of Bill
and Pamela Resch.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RECITAL'S BUST ORCHESTRATED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     It's not that the Resches' Naglee Park neighbors were complaining, either.;
   Nevertheless, as two dozen guests were filing out following the recital, as
Bill Resch was standing in his tuxedo and tails, a San Jose police officer
busted him.;    "I was fingerprinted and cited in full view of my neighbors
and house guests," he complained in a letter to Mayor Susan Hammer and City
Councilman David Pandori. "There was absolutely no warning given. I was told
by the policeman that I was the subject of an ongoing investigation.";
Which leads you to wonder, with cops complaining about being chronically
shorthanded, with neighborhood streets going unpatrolled and violent crimes
going unprevented, how did this Beethoven bust ever come about?;    The first
clue came from an ad in Metro, the San Jose weekly newspaper, inviting
classical music enthusiasts to a Sunday recital. Guests would be greeted at
the door of a restored 19th-century home and treated to a glass of wine as
part of the $25 admission.;     COME TO find out, the cops routinely comb the
weekly newspaper for ads for potential illicit businesses. A shorthanded
police force uses every trick it can.;    Anyway, vice Sgt. Wysuph contacted
the state Alcoholic Beverage Control office, which contacted Resch on June 21
and asked if he was serving wine at the recitals.;    "I told them that we did
not serve wine, but had an open bottle of wine on the buffet and that people
could help themselves if they wanted," Resch said.;    This, Resch was told,
was illegal. He needed a liquor license to serve booze to guests who have been
paying to hear the couple play in their home for the past seven years.;    But
at the recital Sunday, June 23, the Resches informed the guests there would be
no more wine. The next day, they called the ABC to say they were complying. If
their guests wanted wine, they could bring their own.;    Meanwhile, the vice
squad continued its investigation and came up with a stack of offenses.;
The Resches lacked a business license. Their house was not zoned for
commercial (concert) use. They owed back business taxes, even though their
business was not supposed to be a legal business. They owed penalty payments
in addition to their back business taxes.;     ON SUNDAY, July 7, the two vice
officers purchased tickets and joined the other guests who paid to hear Pamela
Resch perform works by Beethoven, Chopin and Liszt.;    After the applause
died, the officers slipped outside, contacted a patrol car and the bust came
down.;    "This shows how efficient the city can be," Councilman Pandori said
sarcastically. "It's surprising that with all the problems that cry out for
attention, the police department spent so much time on this. This is clearly a
case of misplaced priorities.";    Pandori complained to acting Police Chief
Fred Abram. Two days later, Abram ordered the police citation dropped.;
"Clearly, we were out of our sphere of influence," he said.;    So, I asked,
it had nothing to do with the music?;    "No. The officers reported they
thought the music was great," Abram said.;    Maybe the officers' report, or
rather their musical review, will be circulated through City Hall on behalf of
the Resches, who are negotiating to get a business license, clear up their tax
problems and resume their recitals.;    It would lend a touch of class to the
whole farce if the cops who busted the pianists gave them a standing ovation.  </TEXT>
