<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; SANTA-CLARA; COUNTY; CALIFORNIA; CITY; US; POPULATION; SURVEY;
RESULT; .....; ETHNIC; MINORITY; BLACK; HISPANIC; ASIANS-US; STATISTIC  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  San Jose's burgeoning ethnic population is bound to result in greater
political clout for Hispanics and Asians, politicians say, but it is unlikely
that the ethnic makeup of a largely Anglo city council will change right
away.;    "At first blush, it looks like an opportunity for more minority
representation on the city council," said Mayor Susan Hammer, whose city no
longer has an ethnic majority.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CENSUS SHOWS SHIFT IN S.J. ETHNIC MIX  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related Charts on page 3B of the Morning Final.
See related article this page.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Other politicians and those who will be involved in redrawing boundaries
for city council districts said that ethnic power is already in evidence but
that power may not be entirely dependent on electing more members of minority
groups to the council.;    "We're starting to see an increase in influence
throughout the city and county -- and that doesn't necessarily translate into
electing minority candidates in every case, just as long as a candidate has
our best interests at heart," said Pete Carrillo, president of the Latino
Issues Forum of Santa Clara County.;    In fact, Hammer, an Anglo, has made
ethnic diversity and involvement a theme, with forums and rallies and other
ways of encouraging ethnic diversity in city government.;    Nevertheless,
Carrillo's group and the Asian/Pacific Islander-Americans for Fair
Representation have joined to push for redistricting that will give minorities
a better crack at representation on boards, councils, commissions and in state
and federal offices.;    In San Jose, members of so-called minority groups,
taken together, have grown from a 37 percent share of the population in 1980
to a slight majority -- 50.4 percent. Asians -- the fastest-growing ethnic
group, with a 191.4 percent increase -- are concentrated in areas on the north
end of the city and in the central core. The Hispanic population, which grew
41.1 percent, now accounts for more than half the people on the city's east
side and in parts of the central city.;    The 10-member city council has two
non-Anglo members. District 5's Blanca Alvarado is Hispanic. District 7's
George Shirakawa is Hispanic and Japanese-American.;    Both districts,
especially Alvarado's, have significant Hispanic populations.;    In fact,
when the city began electing council members by districts in 1980, an effort
was made to establish District 5 boundaries so that it was likely a Hispanic
would be elected.;    The district boundaries will be redrawn later this year
based on the new census information. The city charter calls for 10 council
districts that split the population evenly among them. That means council
boundaries will have to be shifted to reflect the new-growth areas in the
north and the south, such as Berryessa, Evergreen and Almaden Valley.;
"When you combine the minority population figures and the concentrations of
that population -- that's pretty compelling. . . . In the long term that means
it's likely minorities will tip the scales in elections from school boards to
city councils to higher offices," Carrillo said.;    That appears already to
have happened in the Alum Rock School District, where all five school board
members are Hispanic.;    The Census Bureau uses the term "Hispanic" to
describe people of Latin American or Spanish ancestry. As used by federal
officials, it can include blacks or whites, as well as people of Asian and
American Indian descent.;    The Mercury News has substituted the term "Anglo"
for what the Census Bureau calls "non-Hispanic whites.";    Bob Brownstein, a
longtime participant in local politics, said minority groups can still wield
considerable clout even if they aren't grouped in a single district.;    "A
strong voting minority is better off having 30 percent of its population in
two districts than 60 percent of it in one because the power is spread out,"
Brownstein said.;    An example of that theory is mobile home owners' groups,
which are scattered across the city, but whose members are politically vocal
and active.;    "They're tremendously influential because they affect several
different districts," Brownstein said.;    But if there's a low voter turnout,
he said, "you want them in one district because it takes virtually all of them
to make a difference.";    Traditionally, turnout in District 5 has been half
of that in predominantly Anglo District 10, even though the districts have
roughly the same population.;    So the real challenge is encouraging
participation from the ethnic groups.;    In a multi-ethnic society,
Brownstein said, you have to find a way to involve the biggest group. "There's
hardly a situation where an ethnic majority isn't in power that you don't have
mega-trouble," Brownstein said. "This state's going to be an incredible
political laboratory in the next decade."  </TEXT>
