<LEADPARA>  City officials still want a cut of the action at the Garden City Card Club,
but will reduce their proposed tax take slightly because the card room's
owners complained that San Jose is harder on poker parlors than most other
cities.;   The revised tax lops about 1 percent off the gross receipts tax
that council members will consider Tuesday. Under the new plan, the sliding
tax scale now tops out at 10.5 percent of the club's take.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SAN JOSE OFFERS NEW DEAL IN CARD CLUB TAX PROPOSAL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Aimed at reducing deficit; Designed to help defray a projected $20
million-plus budget deficit, the tax originally was to have been considered by
the council two weeks ago. But the measure was delayed after card room partner
Nicholas J. Dalis and club attorney Frank Nicoletti -- who proposed the tax
earlier this year -- complained that the city wanted too much, council members
said.;   Mayor Susan Hammer's budget staff hopes the tax will raise at least
$2 million annually, although no one is certain of the amount because the club
has never before been required to report its gross receipts to the city.;
Since Hammer's official proposal two weeks ago, the card club has argued that
other highly taxed clubs, most of them in Southern California, are allowed to
offer virtually any game that is legal under state law, which specifically
forbids only 12 games.;   Meant to discourage games; San Jose's card room
ordinance, originally written to discourage the clubs and eventually eliminate
them from the city, allows the club to choose which three of six approved
games it will offer. The choices were written into the ordinance during the
last two years after intense lobbying by Dalis and his family.;   Despite the
reduction in the tax proposal, card room officials still are complaining about
the rules that limit the games they can offer, several city council members
said.;   "It (expansion of the number of games at Garden City) is not on the
agenda, but it really is," acknowledged Councilman Jim Beall, who said he has
not decided how he will vote on the tax.;   At least seven other council
members said they favor the tax, which ensures its passage Tuesday.;
Councilman George Shirakawa said he expects the addition of more games to be
raised in January when the council takes another look at its budget.
Councilwoman Shirley Lewis already has suggested the 40-table club be allowed
to offer anything that is legal under state law. Councilwoman Judy Stabile
said she agrees.;   But Hammer's budget chief, Bob Brownstein, said Friday
that expansion "is not in the cards, from the mayor's perspective.";   That
most likely means the issue will be raised by someone else, though it may not
prove as popular as the tax. Two council members who said they will vote for
the tax, David Pandori and Nancy Ianni, said they will not support any new
games at the club.;   The issue is particularly dicey because Dalis and 10
other club principals face conspiracy and tax charges stemming from an alleged
multimillion-dollar skimming operation. Ten of the 11 also are charged with
violating state campaign contribution laws for allegedly arranging
contributions to politicians to expand the cardroom's political pull. Most
city council members received contributions.;   A trial date has not been set.
But convictions or a plea bargain in the case could result in the loss of the
club's license, which could place the city's newest revenue source in
jeopardy.;   In that case, council members said, the city should collect what
it can while it can.;   "As long as it's there, we should tax it," Ianni said.  </TEXT>
