<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Susan Hammer; ... Calls meeting 'milestone'; PHOTO: Michael
Rondou -- Mercury News; VOCAL PROTEST -- Advocates of more funds for the
homeless booed Mayor Susan Hammer's remarks on the issue of a San Jose stadium.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL; MEETING; SPORT; FACILITY; BUILDING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  After cloistering themselves behind closed doors Friday, members of Mayor
Susan Hammer's stadium commission emerged with a list of "findings" that
surprised no one and left unanswered key questions about the ballpark deal.;
 Instead of going to the San Jose City Council next week as expected, the
report was put on hold until the council returns from its monthlong vacation
in early August.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  REVELATIONS ARE FEW
STADIUM QUESTIONS REMAIN AFTER PRIVATE SESSION  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     So the council will have to work fast if it wants to place a stadium
measure on the November ballot. Hammer said it could also go before voters
next April or June.;    As expected, the commission avoided pinning a price on
the project, working instead with the $160 million estimate developed in last
year's unsuccessful effort to build a Santa Clara stadium for the San
Francisco Giants.;    The commission also declined to say what portion of the
stadium tab taxpayers should bear.;    And, as expected, the commission
reported that:;    (check) The best site is a 138-acre plot near Zanker Road
and Highway 237.;    (check) The city should own the stadium outright or in
partnership with the Giants or some other private entity.;    (check) Odors
from the nearby sewage treatment plant are slight and can be eliminated
easily.;    (check) The city could use a variety of taxes, including a tax on
admissions and parking at the stadium, to help pay the bills. However, the
commission did not say which of the taxes it preferred.;    At a drizzly
afternoon news conference outside City Hall, the mayor hailed the commission's
results as "a very important milestone" in bringing the Giants to San Jose.
Earlier this week, the council tentatively set aside $40 million in
redevelopment money for the stadium.;    Hammer's remarks drew boos and
heckling from a small crowd of placard-toting homeless advocates who want the
city to spend more on housing.;    Asked whether all future stadium meetings
will be public, Hammer said, "I'm not going to make any guarantees.";
Earlier Friday, commission officials barred Mercury News reporters and the
public from their final meeting, despite arguments by the newspaper's
attorneys that closing the meeting violated the Ralph M. Brown Act, the
state's open-meeting law.;    Before and after the meeting, commission members
refused to comment on why the meeting had been closed or they evaded the
issue, insisting that nothing newsworthy was said. None, including elected
officials on the commission, said the meeting should have been open.;    All
other meetings of the 29-member commission have been open to the public.;
Replies ranged from a "no comment" offered by William L. Gates, an aide to
state Sen. Alfred Alquist, to a shrug from Santa Clara County Supervisor Ron
Gonzales.;    "I'm not concerned about it," Gonzales said. "I don't see what
the big issue is, myself.";    Sunnyvale Councilman Larry Stone, who began his
career arguing for open meetings in his hometown, said, "As it turned out, I
wouldn't have been uncomfortable if you (reporters) had been here." But Stone
argued that sensitive financial negotiating points with the Giants might have
been broached during the meeting -- reason enough, he said, to close it.;
Closed meeting opinions;  San Jose Councilman Joe Head agreed with Stone. But
councilmen Jim Beall and David Pandori -- who are not on the commission --
said the meeting should have been open.;    "It's disgusting that an issue of
such public importance was closed to the public," Beall said.;    When closing
of the meeting was announced Thursday, City Attorney Joan Gallo said the move
was legal because the commission is not a legislative body. She cited a
footnote to a 1989 court decision involving a commission appointed by San
Francisco's mayor.;    But Mercury News attorneys Edward P. Davis Jr. and
Donna Timmerman argued that the San Francisco ruling does not apply in San
Jose, where, unlike San Francisco, the mayor is a voting member of the city
council.;    New argument surfaces;  On Friday, however, Gallo offered another
argument for closing the meeting, saying the mayor's commission was nothing
more than a select group of personal advisers.;    "It isn't a board; it isn't
a commission," Gallo said. "They can call them what they want . . . but they
were not appointed by the council.";    Retorted Davis: "We've poked a hole in
her first argument and now she's got another one. I still believe we have a
Brown Act violation.";    Though Gallo argued that Hammer's assembled advisers
are not publicly accountable, the public supports their work in a multitude of
ways, down to the taxpayer-financed doughnuts and coffee provided at weekly
meetings.;    Two deputy city managers staff the group. So do members of the
mayor's office. The group meets in City Hall conference rooms. And the group
used city letterhead to announce its findings.;    "Brown Act or no Brown Act,
there are very few legitimate interests in closing these proceedings," said
Tom Newton, staff attorney for the California Newspaper Publishers
Association. "You've got a highly newsworthy event. Why not open it up?"  </TEXT>
